{"type":"message","id":"ab348994","parentId":"a194276d","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:04:01.868Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Perfeito.\n\n## 1. Missão do `scene_director`\nVou formular primeiro a versão mais provável, só como ponto de partida para ajustarmos:\n\n**Hipótese inicial:**  \no `scene_director` é o operator responsável por transformar o script bruto numa **estrutura de cenas editorialmente inteligente**, definindo como a história deve ser quebrada em unidades visuais/narrativas que depois vão alimentar o resto do pipeline.\n\nAgora vamos afiar isso.\n\n### O que eu quero validar contigo\nEntre estas opções, qual está mais perto do papel real dele?\n\n### A.\nEle **quebra o script em cenas** e define a lógica narrativa/visual de cada uma.\n\n### B.\nEle não só quebra em cenas, mas também **já determina intenção editorial** de cada cena:\n- função dramática\n- ritmo\n- tipo de momento\n- talvez até prioridade visual\n\n### C.\nEle é ainda mais central:\n- interpreta o script\n- decide a gramática da narrativa em cenas\n- e praticamente cria o primeiro “esqueleto criativo” do vídeo\n\n### D.\nOutra definição melhor\n\n---\n\n## Minha leitura preliminar\nEu suspeito que a resposta certa está entre **B e C**.\n\nPorque se ele fosse só “quebrador de texto em cenas”, seria quase uma função mecânica demais.  \nE o nome `scene_director` sugere algo mais próximo de:\n\n- interpretar o texto\n- estruturar a progressão narrativa\n- decidir onde começam/terminam as cenas\n- dar a cada cena uma intenção clara\n\nMas sem ainda invadir o papel de peças posteriores.\n\n---\n\n## Então a pergunta exacta:\n**Numa frase: qual é a missão do `scene_director`?**\n\nSe quiser, podes responder de forma solta mesmo, e eu refino.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaa1add6881948a661e22f804dbfa\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":165,"output":378,"cacheRead":40064,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":40607,"cost":{"input":0.00041250000000000005,"output":0.0056700000000000006,"cacheRead":0.010015999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.016098499999999998}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774955030138,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaa18bb2c8194901b84e295cddb20"}}
{"type":"message","id":"d487b32b","parentId":"ab348994","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:05:12.068Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:05 GMT-3] é isso mesmo Tobias, uma junção do B e C."}],"timestamp":1774955111940}}
{"type":"message","id":"a17a3a2e","parentId":"d487b32b","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:05:24.850Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Óptimo. Então eu transformaria isso numa formulação mais canónica assim:\n\n## Missão do `scene_director`\n**Interpretar o script e transformá-lo no primeiro esqueleto criativo do vídeo, quebrando a narrativa em cenas com intenção editorial clara, de forma que o resto do pipeline saiba o que cada parte da história precisa comunicar e sustentar visualmente.**\n\nQuero destacar porque esta formulação é boa:\n- **“interpretar o script”** → não é segmentação mecânica\n- **“primeiro esqueleto criativo do vídeo”** → mostra que ele é fundacional\n- **“quebrando a narrativa em cenas”** → delimita a unidade de trabalho\n- **“intenção editorial clara”** → o output não é só estrutural, é semântico\n- **“para o resto do pipeline”** → posiciona a peça no sistema, não isoladamente\n\n---\n\n## Consequência importante\nIsso já sugere uma fronteira forte:\n\no `scene_director` **não é apenas um scene splitter**  \ne também **não é ainda o responsável por executar planeamento visual detalhado**.\n\nEle está no meio:\n- mais inteligente que um segmentador\n- mais abstracto que um planner visual de assets/shots\n\n---\n\n# Próxima pergunta: responsabilidade única\nAgora precisamos afiar isto:\n\n## 2. Qual é a decisão central que só o `scene_director` toma?\nEm outras palavras:\n\n**se eu removesse o `scene_director`, qual capacidade específica o sistema perderia?**\n\nMinha hipótese:\n\n> o sistema perderia a capacidade de converter um texto corrido numa sequência de cenas narrativamente intencional, com começo/fim/função claros para cada bloco da história.\n\nMas talvez ainda esteja genérico demais.\n\n### Algumas formulações candidatas\n#### A.\nDecidir **onde as cenas começam e terminam**.\n\n#### B.\nDecidir **como a história deve ser estruturada em unidades dramáticas/visuais**.\n\n#### C.\nDecidir **qual a função narrativa de cada cena** dentro do vídeo.\n\n#### D.\nUma combinação de A + B + C\n\n---\n\n## Minha leitura\nAcho que aqui a resposta correcta também é uma combinação.  \nMas é útil descobrir o **núcleo irredutível**.\n\nPorque se tentarmos dar ao `scene_director` todas as decisões criativas, ele vira uma peça inchada.\n\n### Então a pergunta exacta:\n**Qual é a responsabilidade única e irredutível do `scene_director`?**  \nSe quiser, podes responder do jeito mais bruto possível e eu destilo.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaa6cc7448194b4fc1cebf85c7c86\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":230,"output":553,"cacheRead":40448,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41231,"cost":{"input":0.0005750000000000001,"output":0.008295,"cacheRead":0.010112,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.018982}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774955113178,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaa6c36b48194a31fdb43651ee4dc"}}
{"type":"message","id":"cc0ce650","parentId":"a17a3a2e","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:06:14.258Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:06 GMT-3] po pergunta dificil Tobias me ajuda a responder"}],"timestamp":1774955174183}}
{"type":"message","id":"01d22535","parentId":"cc0ce650","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:06:29.015Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim — essa é mesmo difícil. Vou destrinchar.\n\nA forma certa de responder isso é perguntar:\n\n**qual decisão queremos que nasça exactamente aqui, e não antes nem depois?**\n\nVamos por eliminação.\n\n---\n\n## O que não é a responsabilidade única dele\n\n### Não é só segmentar texto\nSe fosse apenas:\n- “quebrar em cenas”\nisso poderia virar uma função mecânica.\n\nMas tu mesmo já deixaste claro que ele faz mais do que isso.\n\n### Não é planeamento visual detalhado\nEle ainda não devia decidir coisas como:\n- asset específico\n- tipo exacto de imagem\n- prompt de imagem\n- b-roll exacto\n- animação exacta\n- composição final\n\nIsso pertence mais à frente no pipeline.\n\n### Não é polir narração\nTambém não é papel dele:\n- reescrever texto para TTS\n- ajustar prosódia\n- melhorar oralidade da fala\n\nIsso é mais `tts_polish`.\n\n### Não é validar\nEle também não existe primariamente para:\n- auditar conformidade\n- verificar schema\n- reprovar formato\n\nIsso é mais validator/supervisor.\n\n---\n\n# Então o que sobra?\nSobra uma função muito específica e valiosa:\n\n> **dar forma narrativa ao script numa unidade operacional de cenas**\n\nMas ainda podemos afiar melhor.\n\n---\n\n## Minha proposta de responsabilidade única\nEu tentaria algo assim:\n\n**A responsabilidade central do `scene_director` é decidir como o script deve ser convertido em cenas narrativamente intencionais — definindo a divisão e a função de cada cena como primeiro esqueleto criativo do vídeo.**\n\nIsto junta:\n- **divisão** → onde começa e termina\n- **função** → porque essa cena existe\n- **esqueleto criativo** → ele não executa o resto, mas funda o resto\n\n---\n\n## Versão ainda mais curta\nSe quisermos uma frase mais “contratual”:\n\n**Converter o script em uma sequência de cenas com função narrativa clara.**\n\nOu, versão um pouco mais rica:\n\n**Transformar texto corrido em estrutura de cenas editorialmente intencional.**\n\n---\n\n## Como testar se essa é mesmo a responsabilidade certa\nPergunta de teste:\n\nSe o `scene_director` fizer um trabalho excelente, mas o resto do pipeline ainda não rodar,  \n**o que já deveria existir de valioso?**\n\nMinha resposta seria:\n- uma decomposição da história em cenas\n- com fronteiras que fazem sentido\n- com lógica narrativa coerente\n- com função clara por cena\n- pronta para ser desenvolvida depois em bible / visual planning / polish / execução\n\nSe isso bate com o que tu imaginas, então estamos no caminho certo.\n\n---\n\n# Minha sugestão\nEu proporia fixar assim por enquanto:\n\n## Responsabilidade única do `scene_director`\n**Transformar o script numa sequência de cenas editorialmente intencional, definindo a divisão e a função narrativa de cada cena como primeiro esqueleto criativo do vídeo.**\n\nSe tu quiser, o próximo passo é:\n## 3. O que ele recebe de input exactamente?\nPorque aí a peça começa a ficar muito concreta.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaaaabe78819482cc6d87ccbf8d97\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":209,"output":660,"cacheRead":41088,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":41957,"cost":{"input":0.0005225000000000001,"output":0.0099,"cacheRead":0.010272,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0206945}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774955175270,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaaaa25b08194a35915367260e5be"}}
{"type":"message","id":"c065f8aa","parentId":"01d22535","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:07:37.037Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:07 GMT-3] Transformar o script numa sequência de cenas editorialmente intencional, definindo a divisão e a função narrativa de cada cena como primeiro esqueleto criativo do vídeo. Perfeito, concordo completamente. 3. O que ele recebe de input exactamente? > Acho que consegues já trazer essa repsost6a com base no que já fizemos pro supervbisor né?"}],"timestamp":1774955256925}}
{"type":"message","id":"2879edea","parentId":"c065f8aa","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:07:55.573Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim — aqui já dá para eu propor com bastante confiança com base no que consolidámos no S1.\n\n## 3. Input do `scene_director`\n\n### Minha proposta principal\nO `scene_director` deve receber **o texto do script já seleccionado para o run**, em forma suficientemente limpa/estruturada para ele trabalhar a segmentação narrativa, mas **antes** de qualquer polish de TTS.\n\nOu seja, o input-base dele é:\n\n- **script do vídeo**\n- **metadados mínimos do job/run**\n- possivelmente **algum contexto editorial do canal/conta/idioma**\n- mas **não** dependente ainda de outputs de operators posteriores\n\n---\n\n# O que eu acho que entra com segurança\n\n## Input nuclear\n### 1. Texto integral do script\nIsto é o coração.\n\nSem isso ele não consegue:\n- interpretar a progressão narrativa\n- decidir fronteiras de cena\n- atribuir função narrativa\n\nEntão o script completo tem de entrar.\n\n### 2. Identidade do contexto do vídeo\nAlgo como:\n- conta/canal\n- idioma\n- talvez `job_id` / `run_id`\n\nIsto não serve para ele “gerir ficheiros”, mas para contextualizar:\n- estilo geral do canal\n- idioma da narrativa\n- possíveis constraints do formato\n\n### 3. Contexto editorial mínimo\nAqui é onde eu quero ser preciso.\n\nAcho provável que ele deva receber **alguma camada de contexto do canal**, mas **mínima e relevante**, por exemplo:\n- tipo de canal / tema\n- língua\n- talvez natureza do vídeo\n- talvez alguns princípios editoriais do projecto\n\nMas eu **não** acho que ele deva receber um pacote gigante de contexto operacional.\n\nPorque senão o operator vira uma peça excessivamente condicionada e poluída.\n\n---\n\n# O que eu acho que ele não deve precisar de input\n\n## Não deve depender de:\n- timestamps\n- áudio gerado\n- scene bible pronta\n- asset inventory\n- prompts de imagem\n- decisões de composição\n- validações posteriores\n- texto já polido para TTS\n\nIsto ajuda a manter a fronteira limpa.\n\n---\n\n# Formulação contratual provisória\n\n## Input do `scene_director`\n**O `scene_director` recebe o script integral do vídeo, junto com metadados essenciais do run e contexto editorial mínimo do canal/idioma, para poder interpretar a narrativa e convertê-la numa sequência de cenas com intenção clara.**\n\n---\n\n# Em formato mais operacional\nSe eu traduzisse isso para campos conceptuais, seria algo como:\n\n- `script_text`\n- `language`\n- `channel/account identity`\n- `job/run metadata`\n- `editorial context` mínimo, se existir\n\n---\n\n# Ponto importante de fronteira\nEu acho importante decidir contigo isto:\n\n## O `scene_director` recebe o script em que estado?\n### opção A\n**script bruto vindo do VO / fetch**\n- vantagem: ele trabalha sobre a matéria-prima real\n- desvantagem: pode vir com ruído\n\n### opção B\n**script já normalizado/limpo deterministicamente**\n- vantagem: menos ruído operacional\n- desvantagem: precisamos definir essa camada de normalização\n\n### opção C\n**script já parcialmente preparado semanticamente**\n- eu tenderia a dizer **não**, para não contaminar o papel dele\n\n---\n\n## Minha recomendação\nA melhor formulação por enquanto é:\n\n> ele recebe o **script integral já carregado/normalizado no run**, mas **antes de qualquer transformação semântica como tts_polish**\n\nIsto me parece o ponto mais limpo.\n\n---\n\nSe quiser, eu já transformo isso numa resposta fechada de contrato, e passamos para a próxima:\n\n## 4. O que exactamente ele devolve de output?","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaafee1b08194b1da27accd5275e2\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":239,"output":796,"cacheRead":41856,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":42891,"cost":{"input":0.0005975,"output":0.011940000000000001,"cacheRead":0.010464,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0230015}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774955258005,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbaafce9288194afc6b8718709740e"}}
{"type":"message","id":"b3bdafcb","parentId":"2879edea","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:10:31.406Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:10 GMT-3] mas e o fato de o scene director não receber o script inteiro em apenas uma chamada Tobias? Nós já definimos isso no supervisor né. Leia lá o que fizemos por supervisor poxa C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1_supervisor_contract.md C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\runtime\\s1\\supervisor_skills"}],"timestamp":1774955431331}}
{"type":"message","id":"103bb84c","parentId":"b3bdafcb","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:10:36.007Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabad1ae08194a7e9579144e5cce9\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_L0FOUR9iaT9cuGX5ZcaoPvuY|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabad5ab881948e3ff20e1e6d58c2","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1_supervisor_contract.md"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1_supervisor_contract.md\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":286,"output":45,"cacheRead":42752,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":43083,"cost":{"input":0.000715,"output":0.000675,"cacheRead":0.010688,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.012078}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774955432443,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabab58c4819497784320dac985e7"}}
{"type":"message","id":"93e1d6be","parentId":"103bb84c","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:10:36.581Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_L0FOUR9iaT9cuGX5ZcaoPvuY|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabad5ab881948e3ff20e1e6d58c2","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"# S1 Supervisor Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and first deterministic skill of the S1 (Pre-Production) Supervisor._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-30_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is the supervisory layer for Pre-Production.\n\nIts job is to take a run that is `ready_for_s1` and coordinate the sector until it produces:\n- `screenplay.json`\n- `screenplay_validation.json`\n- `tts_polished.json`\n- `polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `b1_*` checkpoints\n\nThe supervisor is an **OpenClaw LLM supervisor**, not a purely conversational helper and not a monolithic Python script that absorbs all work itself.\n\nIt should supervise using:\n- deterministic Python skills\n- specialized operators/sub-agents\n- explicit file contracts\n\n---\n\n## Core principle\n\n### Supervisor = brain\n### Skills = hands\n### Operators = specialists\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- decide the order of operations\n- decide when to call an operator vs a deterministic skill\n- interpret validation results\n- decide retry / fail / continue\n- write or trigger checkpoints\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should **not** directly absorb:\n- semantic scene generation\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path mechanics\n- deterministic validation logic\n- JSON merge/reindex mechanics\n\nThose belong to:\n- S1 operators (`scene_director`, `tts_polish`)\n- deterministic supervisor skills\n\n---\n\n## Current operator model\n\nThe current intended operator structure for S1 is:\n- `scene_director` -> OpenClaw operator\n- `tts_polish` -> OpenClaw operator\n\nThese operators communicate with the supervisor via explicit file contracts:\n- supervisor prepares input payload/file\n- operator reads input\n- operator writes output file\n- supervisor validates and decides next step\n\n## Controlled parallelism policy\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should support controlled parallelism for batchable operators.\n\n### Initial recommended concurrency caps\n- `scene_director_concurrency_cap = 2`\n- `tts_polish_concurrency_cap = 4`\n\n### Parallelism rules\n- only batchable operators should be parallelized\n- validators, mergers, builders, and preflight remain sequential/deterministic\n- the supervisor should not launch all batches at once without a cap\n- batches should be processed in controlled waves/windows\n- failed batches should be retried selectively when possible via `retry_planner`\n\n---\n\n## Current deterministic skills owned by the supervisor\n\n### Implemented now\n- `s1_preflight_checker`\n- `s1_paths_resolver`\n- `script_batch_planner`\n- `scene_director_io_adapter`\n- `screenplay_merger`\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n- `tts_polish_merger`\n- `retry_planner`\n- `s1_result_summarizer`\n- `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\n### Expected next skills\n- `checkpoint_writer` (already exists in `runtime/s1/checkpoint_writer.py`, pending light alignment audit only)\n\nThis list may evolve, but the supervisor should remain supervisory rather than mechanically overloaded.\n\n---\n\n## File contract principle\n\nThe supervisor must operate on persisted run artifacts.\n\nMinimum expected inputs before S1 begins:\n- `job.json`\n- `run_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_raw.txt`\n- `inputs/script/script_metadata.json`\n- `inputs/script/script_lock.json`\n- `checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json`\n\nMinimum expected outputs after S1 completes:\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/screenplay_validation.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json`\n- `b1_pre_production/polish_validation.json`\n- `scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step1_screenplay.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step2_screenplay_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step3_tts_polished.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step4_polish_validated.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_step5_scene_bible.json`\n- `checkpoints/b1_complete.json`\n\n---\n\n## First implemented supervisor skill: `s1_preflight_checker`\n\n### Purpose\nValidate that a run is structurally ready to enter S1 before any operator or semantic step is invoked.\n\n### Scope\nChecks:\n- run root exists\n- required input files exist\n- `job.json` is readable and contains `job_id`, `account`, `language`\n- channel config exists at `accounts/{account}/{language}.yaml`\n- `script_raw.txt` is readable and not empty\n- `vo_script_ready` checkpoint exists\n- run state is minimally compatible with entering S1\n\n### Out of scope\n`s1_preflight_checker` does **not**:\n- create sector outputs\n- call operators\n- validate screenplay semantics\n- decide batching\n- modify the run\n\n### Input shape\n```json\n{\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\"\n}\n```\n\n### Output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n  \"job\": {\n    \"job_id\": \"2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n    \"account\": \"004\",\n    \"language\": \"fr\"\n  },\n  \"paths\": {\n    \"job_json\": \".../job.json\",\n    \"run_metadata\": \".../run_metadata.json\",\n    \"script_raw\": \".../inputs/script/script_raw.txt\",\n    \"script_metadata\": \".../inputs/script/script_metadata.json\",\n    \"script_lock\": \".../inputs/script/script_lock.json\",\n    \"vo_script_ready_checkpoint\": \".../checkpoints/vo_script_ready.json\",\n    \"channel_config\": \".../accounts/004/fr.yaml\"\n  },\n  \"script_stats\": {\n    \"char_count\": 0,\n    \"word_count\": 0\n  },\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n### Error policy\nThe skill should collect all relevant failures and return them together.\nIt should not stop at the first missing file.\n\n### Warning policy\nExamples of warning-worthy but non-fatal conditions:\n- script very short\n- script very long\n- `b1_pre_production/` already exists but `b1_complete.json` does not\n\n### Fatal examples\n- missing `job.json`\n- missing `script_raw.txt`\n- unreadable or invalid `job.json`\n- missing channel config\n- missing `vo_script_ready.json`\n- empty script\n\n---\n\n## Naming convention\nThe canonical checkpoint and sector naming for Pre-Production is:\n- `b1_pre_production/`\n- `b1_*` checkpoints\n\nThe older `s1_*` naming should not be treated as canonical.\n\n---\n\n## Second implemented supervisor skill: `s1_paths_resolver`\n\n### Purpose\nResolve and centralize the canonical S1 paths for the run.\n\n### Scope\nResolves and optionally creates the directory structure for:\n- `b1_pre_production/`\n- `b1_pre_production/inputs/`\n- `b1_pre_production/intermediate/`\n- `inputs/scene_director/`\n- `inputs/tts_polish/`\n- `intermediate/scene_director/`\n- `intermediate/tts_polish/`\n- canonical output file paths\n- canonical `b1_*` checkpoint file paths\n\n### Out of scope\n`s1_paths_resolver` does **not**:\n- validate semantic readiness\n- call operators\n- inspect screenplay or polish content\n- perform batching\n\n### Input shape\n```json\n{\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n  \"create_dirs\": true\n}\n```\n\n### Output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"run_root\": \"C:/.../production/004_fr/2026-03-30_004_fr_001\",\n  \"created_dirs\": true,\n  \"paths\": {\n    \"b1_root\": \".../b1_pre_production\",\n    \"inputs_root\": \".../b1_pre_production/inputs\",\n    \"intermediate_root\": \".../b1_pre_production/intermediate\",\n    \"screenplay_path\": \".../b1_pre_production/screenplay.json\",\n    \"tts_polished_path\": \".../b1_pre_production/tts_polished.json\",\n    \"scene_bible_path\": \".../scene_bible.json\",\n    \"b1_complete_checkpoint\": \".../checkpoints/b1_complete.json\"\n  },\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n## Third implemented supervisor skill: `script_batch_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nSplit the raw script into manageable work batches for `scene_director` without turning the supervisor into a monolithic batching script.\n\n### Scope\n- receives raw script text or script file path\n- plans batches using target/min/max word budgets\n- prefers paragraph boundaries\n- falls back to sentence-based splitting for oversized paragraphs\n- preserves order and emits a stable `sd_###` batch sequence\n\n### Out of scope\n`script_batch_planner` does **not**:\n- divide the script into final scenes\n- call `scene_director`\n- perform semantic validation\n- merge operator outputs\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target words per batch: `750`\n- minimum words per batch: `450`\n- maximum words per batch: `950`\n\n### Output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"total_words\": 3520,\n  \"batch_count\": 5,\n  \"target_words_per_batch\": 750,\n  \"min_words_per_batch\": 450,\n  \"max_words_per_batch\": 950,\n  \"batches\": [\n    {\n      \"batch_id\": \"sd_001\",\n      \"start_word\": 1,\n      \"end_word\": 742,\n      \"word_count\": 742,\n      \"text\": \"...\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": []\n}\n```\n\n## Fourth implemented supervisor skill: `scene_director_io_adapter`\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the explicit input/output contract between the S1 Supervisor and the `scene_director` operator for each planned script batch.\n\n### Scope\n- receives run/job context\n- receives one script batch from `script_batch_planner`\n- injects `scene_words_range` from channel config\n- writes a deterministic payload file for the operator\n- declares the expected output path for the batch result\n\n### Out of scope\n`scene_director_io_adapter` does **not**:\n- run the operator\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge batch outputs\n- choose retry policy\n\n### Output contract principle\nEach batch payload should explicitly tell `scene_director`:\n- who the run/job is\n- what the batch text is\n- what scene structure is expected\n- where to write the result\n\n## Fifth implemented supervisor skill: `screenplay_merger`\n\n### Purpose\nMerge the batch outputs of `scene_director` into one canonical `screenplay.json` without forcing the supervisor itself to concatenate, validate, and reindex scene objects manually.\n\n### Scope\n- loads ordered batch output files\n- validates minimum required scene fields\n- concatenates scenes in batch order\n- reassigns canonical `scene_###` IDs globally\n- writes `screenplay.json`\n\n### Out of scope\n`screenplay_merger` does **not**:\n- perform semantic validation\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- polish TTS text\n\n### Output contract principle\nThe merged screenplay should preserve order while normalizing scene IDs into one canonical sequence for the rest of S1.\n\n## Sixth implemented supervisor skill: `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nPlan small, stable polish batches from the merged screenplay so that `tts_polish` receives manageable groups of scenes instead of the full screenplay at once.\n\n### Scope\n- receives `screenplay.json`\n- groups scenes by count and approximate word budget\n- preserves scene order\n- emits a stable `tp_###` batch sequence\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target scenes per batch: `5`\n- minimum scenes per batch: `3`\n- maximum scenes per batch: `6`\n- maximum words per batch: `350`\n\n### Out of scope\n`tts_polish_batch_planner` does **not**:\n- perform TTS polish\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge polish outputs\n- decide retry policy\n\n## Seventh implemented supervisor skill: `tts_polish_io_adapter`\n\n### Purpose\nPrepare the explicit input/output contract between the S1 Supervisor and the `tts_polish` operator for each planned polish batch.\n\n### Scope\n- receives run/job context\n- receives merged screenplay\n- receives one polish batch from `tts_polish_batch_planner`\n- injects `tts_polish_rules` from channel config\n- writes a deterministic payload file for the operator\n- declares the expected output path for the batch result\n\n### Out of scope\n`tts_polish_io_adapter` does **not**:\n- run the operator\n- validate semantic quality\n- merge polish outputs\n- choose retry policy\n\n### Output contract principle\nEach polish batch payload should explicitly tell `tts_polish`:\n- which scenes belong to the batch\n- what the original narration is\n- what rules govern polish behavior\n- where to write the result\n\n## Eighth implemented supervisor skill: `tts_polish_merger`\n\n### Purpose\nMerge the batch outputs of `tts_polish` into one canonical `tts_polished.json` while preserving screenplay order and preserving the distinction between original narration and TTS-polished narration.\n\n### Scope\n- loads ordered polish batch files\n- validates minimum required polish scene fields\n- rebuilds one ordered `tts_polished.json`\n- uses screenplay order as the canonical scene sequence\n\n### Out of scope\n`tts_polish_merger` does **not**:\n- validate semantic quality of the polish\n- decide retry policy\n- invoke operators\n- overwrite the original screenplay artifact\n\n### Output contract principle\nThe merged polish output should preserve:\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\nwithout destroying the original screenplay layer.\n\n## Ninth implemented supervisor skill: `retry_planner`\n\n### Purpose\nTurn observed failures into explicit retry decisions so the S1 Supervisor can decide whether to abort, rerun a whole step, or rerun only affected batches.\n\n### Scope\n- classifies failure types into retry strategies\n- enforces retry limits\n- supports fail-fast structural errors\n- supports batch-subset retries for localized operator/semantic failures\n- supports step-level retries when failures are broader\n\n### Out of scope\n`retry_planner` does **not**:\n- run retries itself\n- inspect semantic payloads deeply\n- invoke operators or validators\n- write checkpoints\n\n### Decision categories in v1\n- `abort`\n- `step`\n- `batch_subset`\n\n## Tenth implemented supervisor skill: `s1_result_summarizer`\n\n### Purpose\nProduce the final structured sector result that the S1 Supervisor can return upward after the sector finishes or fails.\n\n### Scope\n- aggregates scene counts\n- aggregates batch counts\n- exposes `scene_bible_path`\n- exposes checkpoint list\n- determines final `status` / `next_step`\n- preserves warnings/errors in one final result object\n\n### Out of scope\n`s1_result_summarizer` does **not**:\n- run the sector\n- write checkpoints\n- validate semantic correctness\n- call operators or skills\n\n## Eleventh implemented supervisor skill: `operator_batch_scheduler`\n\n### Purpose\nProvide the controlled parallelism layer for batchable operators so the supervisor can launch work in capped waves instead of all-at-once or fully sequentially.\n\n### Scope\n- receives operator batches\n- applies a concurrency cap\n- groups batches into execution waves\n- summarizes execution outcomes into completed / failed / pending sets\n\n### Initial supported operators\n- `scene_director`\n- `tts_polish`\n\n### Out of scope\n`operator_batch_scheduler` does **not**:\n- invoke OpenClaw operators by itself yet\n- decide semantic retry logic\n- merge outputs\n- validate content\n\n## Current status summary\nAt this stage:\n- the S1 Supervisor is defined as an OpenClaw LLM supervisor\n- deterministic helper skills are being formalized\n- `s1_preflight_checker` is implemented as the entry gate for the sector\n- `s1_paths_resolver` is implemented as the canonical path/structure resolver for the sector\n- `script_batch_planner` is implemented as the first batching/planning skill for the sector\n- `scene_director_io_adapter` is implemented as the explicit batch contract bridge to the `scene_director` operator\n- `screenplay_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for batch screenplay outputs\n- `tts_polish_batch_planner` is implemented as the batching/planning layer for `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish_io_adapter` is implemented as the explicit batch contract bridge to the `tts_polish` operator\n- `tts_polish_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for batch polish outputs\n- `retry_planner` is implemented as the retry decision layer for the supervisor\n- `s1_result_summarizer` is implemented as the final sector result aggregation layer\n- `operator_batch_scheduler` is implemented as the controlled parallel scheduling layer for batchable operators\n"}],"isError":false,"timestamp":1774955436455}}
{"type":"message","id":"40ca7603","parentId":"93e1d6be","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:10:39.335Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_ytDzNTgPATLn6cdNHOlxM4U6|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabb087c48194acafb28b8607759a","name":"read","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/runtime/s1/supervisor_skills","offset":1,"limit":200},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/runtime/s1/supervisor_skills\",\"offset\":1,\"limit\":200}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":3858,"output":46,"cacheRead":42880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":46784,"cost":{"input":0.009645,"output":0.00069,"cacheRead":0.01072,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.021055}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774955437093,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabafbd948194bcb779512a39e796"}}
{"type":"message","id":"f8ad3671","parentId":"40ca7603","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:10:39.923Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_ytDzNTgPATLn6cdNHOlxM4U6|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabb087c48194acafb28b8607759a","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"{\n  \"status\": \"error\",\n  \"tool\": \"read\",\n  \"error\": \"EISDIR: illegal operation on a directory, read\"\n}"}],"details":{"status":"error","tool":"read","error":"EISDIR: illegal operation on a directory, read"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774955439792}}
{"type":"message","id":"2ad20e8a","parentId":"f8ad3671","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:10:59.236Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Tens razão — aqui eu comecei a responder num nível demasiado genérico e ignorei uma definição importante que **já estava resolvida no supervisor**.\n\nLi o `s1_supervisor_contract.md` e ele deixa isto muito claro:\n\n## Correcção importante\nO `scene_director` **não recebe o script inteiro numa chamada única**.\n\nO que o supervisor já definiu é:\n\n- existe um **`script_batch_planner`**\n- ele divide o script bruto em **batches geríveis**\n- com sequência estável tipo `sd_001`, `sd_002`, etc.\n- preferindo limites por parágrafo / frase\n- e o `scene_director` trabalha **por batch**, não no script completo de uma vez\n\nAlém disso:\n- existe um **`scene_director_io_adapter`**\n- o supervisor prepara um **payload explícito por batch**\n- injecta `scene_words_range` da config do canal\n- escreve um ficheiro determinístico de input\n- e declara também o **output path esperado** daquele batch\n\nOu seja, a resposta correcta para o input dele não é “o script inteiro”, mas sim:\n\n# Input correcto do `scene_director`\n**O `scene_director` recebe um batch do script, preparado pelo supervisor, dentro de um contrato explícito de I/O por batch — não o script inteiro numa única chamada.**\n\n---\n\n## Mais concretamente, o que entra\nCom base no contrato do supervisor, o input dele deve conter algo nesta linha:\n\n- contexto do **run/job**\n- identificação do **batch** (`sd_001`, etc.)\n- **texto daquele batch**\n- intervalo / metadados do batch\n  - `start_word`\n  - `end_word`\n  - `word_count`\n- regra estrutural esperada\n- `scene_words_range` vindo da config do canal\n- path onde o output daquele batch deve ser escrito\n\n---\n\n## Isto é importante porque muda a natureza da peça\nO `scene_director` não está a “dirigir o vídeo inteiro de uma vez”.\n\nEle está a fazer uma tarefa mais precisa:\n- receber um **trecho narrativo contínuo**\n- transformá-lo em **cenas locais com intenção editorial**\n- respeitando um envelope estrutural definido pelo supervisor\n- para depois isso ser **merged** no `screenplay.json`\n\nE isso casa directamente com o `screenplay_merger`, que:\n- junta outputs dos batches\n- preserva ordem\n- reindexa `scene_###`\n- escreve o `screenplay.json` canónico\n\n---\n\n# Então a formulação melhor da secção 3 seria:\n\n## Input do `scene_director`\n**O `scene_director` recebe um batch do script — não o script inteiro — preparado pelo S1 Supervisor através de um contrato explícito de I/O. Esse input inclui o texto do batch, contexto essencial do run/job, metadados do batch, constraints estruturais relevantes (como `scene_words_range`) e o output path esperado para o resultado daquele batch.**\n\n---\n\n## Insight estrutural importante\nIsto também ajuda a responder uma coisa implícita:\n\no `scene_director` não é responsável por:\n- decidir batching\n- decidir paralelismo\n- decidir merge global\n- gerir continuidade global sozinho\n\nEssas responsabilidades ficam distribuídas assim:\n- **supervisor / skills determinísticas** → batching, scheduling, I/O contract, merge\n- **scene_director** → transformar **cada batch** em cenas editorialmente intencionais\n\n---\n\nSe quiser, agora seguimos para a próxima pergunta já muito melhor ancorada:\n\n## 4. O que exactamente o `scene_director` devolve em cada batch?","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabb6df708194a8bc9303ff668eb2\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":235,"output":766,"cacheRead":46592,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":47593,"cost":{"input":0.0005875,"output":0.01149,"cacheRead":0.011647999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.023725499999999997}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774955440482,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbabb3af48819480ad34eb553c7de8"}}
{"type":"message","id":"add07f70","parentId":"2ad20e8a","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:12:21.460Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:12 GMT-3] Boa Tobias boa. Tu acha que já não vale a pena criar o contract dele pra ir adicionando esses pontos conforme vamos discutindo e definindo?"}],"timestamp":1774955541382}}
{"type":"message","id":"813f64b1","parentId":"add07f70","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:12:35.597Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Sim — **acho que já vale muito a pena**.\n\nNa verdade, este é exactamente o momento certo.\n\nPorque agora já temos:\n- missão\n- responsabilidade central\n- um ponto importante de input já corrigido pelo contrato do supervisor\n\nOu seja, já existe material suficiente para começar um **contract do `scene_director`** sem esperar “fechar tudo”.\n\n## Porque vale a pena criar já\n### 1. Evita perder definições enquanto discutimos\nSenão acontece o clássico:\n- a conversa avança\n- definimos coisas boas\n- depois alguma nuance se perde\n- e mais tarde reconstruímos torto\n\n### 2. Obriga a formular melhor\nQuando passamos para contract:\n- ambiguidades saltam aos olhos\n- lacunas ficam visíveis\n- fronteiras ficam mais fáceis de testar\n\n### 3. Mantém o processo igual ao que funcionou no supervisor\nFoi isso que deu certo no S1 supervisor:\n- discutir\n- escrever contrato\n- refinar\n- só depois pensar mais fundo na implementação\n\n### 4. Ajuda a separar “peça canónica” de “implementação temporária”\nEspecialmente no `scene_director`, isso é importante, porque não queremos que a implementação provisória vire definição por acidente.\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação\n## Sim: criar já o contract dele.\nE ir preenchendo **conforme definimos**.\n\n### O mecanismo que eu usaria\nAqui eu **não usaria `TASKS.md` nem heartbeat**.\n\nIsto é:\n- **trabalho de definição estrutural activo**\n- feito **junto contigo agora**\n- com output documental directo no repo\n\nEntão o mecanismo correcto aqui é:\n- **editar/criar o ficheiro de contract no repo**\n- e evoluir o documento iterativamente durante a conversa\n\n---\n\n# O que eu criaria\nProvavelmente algo como:\n\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\scene_director_contract.md`\n\nou, se quiseres manter naming muito alinhado com o sector:\n`...docs/contracts/s1_scene_director_contract.md`\n\n## Minha preferência\nEu tenderia a usar:\n\n**`s1_scene_director_contract.md`**\n\nporque:\n- cola melhor com `s1_supervisor_contract.md`\n- deixa claro a que sector pertence\n- evita ambiguidade futura se houver outros “directors” noutros sectores\n\n---\n\n# Estrutura inicial que eu proporia\nAlgo simples, ainda incompleto:\n\n- Purpose\n- Core responsibility\n- Position inside S1\n- Input contract\n- Output contract\n- Boundaries / Out of scope\n- Relationship with supervisor\n- Batch model\n- Quality bar\n- Open questions\n\n---\n\n## Minha recomendação concreta\nSe tu quiseres, eu faço agora isto:\n1. **crio o ficheiro**\n2. já escrevo nele o que definimos até aqui:\n   - missão\n   - responsabilidade central\n   - modelo por batch\n   - input preliminar\n3. deixo secções em aberto para irmos preenchendo juntos\n\nAcho que este é o movimento certo.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbac199dc481948ea644178c712d2e\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":193,"output":657,"cacheRead":47488,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":48338,"cost":{"input":0.0004825,"output":0.009855000000000001,"cacheRead":0.011871999999999999,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0222095}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774955542411,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbac18f6748194bdf72e0f1c5d7728"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1ddc9643","parentId":"813f64b1","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:13:39.299Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:13 GMT-3] s1_scene_director_contract.md > Concordo, pode criar lá."}],"timestamp":1774955619220}}
{"type":"message","id":"0f29d827","parentId":"1ddc9643","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:14:01.164Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbac67db608194a1c6a987046568db\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_KW1g9qXiHsTlNBeX5jGrFqFo|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbac6836f481948a4000fdc53599b0","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1_scene_director_contract.md","content":"# S1 Scene Director Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `scene_director` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._ \n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `scene_director` is the S1 operator responsible for interpreting the script and transforming it into the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nIts job is to convert script material into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining scene boundaries and the narrative function of each scene in a way that gives the rest of the pipeline a clear structural base.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `scene_director` is:\n\n> Transform the script into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining the division and narrative function of each scene as the first creative skeleton of the video.\n\nThis means `scene_director` is not just a text splitter. It is the operator that gives narrative shape to the script at the scene level.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nWithin S1, `scene_director` is the first semantic/creative operator.\n\nIts output is the foundational scene structure that will later be:\n- validated\n- merged into canonical sector artifacts\n- used by downstream S1 steps such as polish and scene bible construction\n\n`scene_director` does not own the whole sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Batch execution model\n\n`scene_director` does **not** receive the entire script in one call.\n\nInstead:\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `script_batch_planner` to split the raw script into manageable batches\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`sd_001`, `sd_002`, ...)\n- the supervisor uses `scene_director_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\n- `scene_director` operates on one batch at a time\n- downstream deterministic logic merges batch outputs into canonical `screenplay.json`\n\nThis keeps batching, scheduling, and merge logic out of the operator itself.\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nFor each invocation, `scene_director` should receive a supervisor-prepared batch payload rather than the full script.\n\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity (`sd_###`)\n- batch text\n- batch range metadata (`start_word`, `end_word`, `word_count`)\n- structural constraints relevant to scene generation\n- `scene_words_range` injected from channel config\n- explicit output path for the batch result\n\nThe operator should receive enough context to interpret the batch well, but should not be overloaded with unrelated downstream concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`scene_director` should **not** be responsible for:\n- planning script batches\n- deciding parallelism/concurrency strategy\n- merging batch outputs globally\n- validating sector completion\n- TTS polish generation\n- low-level file/path orchestration\n- final asset planning, prompt writing, or visual execution details\n\nIt also should not collapse into a purely mechanical splitter. Its role is semantic and editorial, but still bounded.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\n- preparing the batch payload\n- deciding when `scene_director` is called\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\n- validating/merging downstream artifacts\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\n\n`scene_director` is responsible for producing the batch-level scene structure output expected by the supervisor contract.\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nTBD.\n\nOpen questions still to define:\n- exact structure of the batch output\n- required scene fields per batch\n- whether narration text is preserved scene-by-scene at this stage\n- whether the operator writes scene rationale explicitly or only implicit scene function\n- what level of continuity metadata is needed across batches\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nTBD.\n\nOpen questions still to define:\n- what makes a batch output “good enough”\n- how scene boundaries should be judged\n- what kinds of editorial mistakes are most important to avoid\n- how much structural freedom the operator should have inside each batch\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the mission of `scene_director`\n- its central responsibility\n- its position as the first semantic operator inside S1\n- its batch-based execution model under supervisor control\n- the current draft of its input contract\n\nThe next step is to define the output contract and the exact scene object expectations.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1_scene_director_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 Scene Director Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `scene_director` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._ \\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `scene_director` is the S1 operator responsible for interpreting the script and transforming it into the first creative skeleton of the video.\\n\\nIts job is to convert script material into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining scene boundaries and the narrative function of each scene in a way that gives the rest of the pipeline a clear structural base.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Core responsibility\\n\\nThe central responsibility of `scene_director` is:\\n\\n> Transform the script into an editorially intentional sequence of scenes, defining the division and narrative function of each scene as the first creative skeleton of the video.\\n\\nThis means `scene_director` is not just a text splitter. It is the operator that gives narrative shape to the script at the scene level.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nWithin S1, `scene_director` is the first semantic/creative operator.\\n\\nIts output is the foundational scene structure that will later be:\\n- validated\\n- merged into canonical sector artifacts\\n- used by downstream S1 steps such as polish and scene bible construction\\n\\n`scene_director` does not own the whole sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Batch execution model\\n\\n`scene_director` does **not** receive the entire script in one call.\\n\\nInstead:\\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `script_batch_planner` to split the raw script into manageable batches\\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`sd_001`, `sd_002`, ...)\\n- the supervisor uses `scene_director_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\\n- `scene_director` operates on one batch at a time\\n- downstream deterministic logic merges batch outputs into canonical `screenplay.json`\\n\\nThis keeps batching, scheduling, and merge logic out of the operator itself.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Input contract (current draft)\\n\\nFor each invocation, `scene_director` should receive a supervisor-prepared batch payload rather than the full script.\\n\\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\\n- run/job context\\n- batch identity (`sd_###`)\\n- batch text\\n- batch range metadata (`start_word`, `end_word`, `word_count`)\\n- structural constraints relevant to scene generation\\n- `scene_words_range` injected from channel config\\n- explicit output path for the batch result\\n\\nThe operator should receive enough context to interpret the batch well, but should not be overloaded with unrelated downstream concerns.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Boundaries / out of scope\\n\\n`scene_director` should **not** be responsible for:\\n- planning script batches\\n- deciding parallelism/concurrency strategy\\n- merging batch outputs globally\\n- validating sector completion\\n- TTS polish generation\\n- low-level file/path orchestration\\n- final asset planning, prompt writing, or visual execution details\\n\\nIt also should not collapse into a purely mechanical splitter. Its role is semantic and editorial, but still bounded.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\\n\\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\\n- preparing the batch payload\\n- deciding when `scene_director` is called\\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\\n- validating/merging downstream artifacts\\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\\n\\n`scene_director` is responsible for producing the batch-level scene structure output expected by the supervisor contract.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output contract\\n\\nTBD.\\n\\nOpen questions still to define:\\n- exact structure of the batch output\\n- required scene fields per batch\\n- whether narration text is preserved scene-by-scene at this stage\\n- whether the operator writes scene rationale explicitly or only implicit scene function\\n- what level of continuity metadata is needed across batches\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Quality bar\\n\\nTBD.\\n\\nOpen questions still to define:\\n- what makes a batch output “good enough”\\n- how scene boundaries should be judged\\n- what kinds of editorial mistakes are most important to avoid\\n- how much structural freedom the operator should have inside each batch\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current status\\n\\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\\n- the mission of `scene_director`\\n- its central responsibility\\n- its position as the first semantic operator inside S1\\n- its batch-based execution model under supervisor control\\n- the current draft of its input contract\\n\\nThe next step is to define the output contract and the exact scene object expectations.\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":155,"output":1060,"cacheRead":48256,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":49471,"cost":{"input":0.00038750000000000004,"output":0.0159,"cacheRead":0.012064,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0283515}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774955620424,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbac67174881948f64e1a60e5034be"}}
