{"type":"message","id":"1984394d","parentId":"1df5e11e","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:44:49.719Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_X1gq7R6QiXqP5CQwxz4EfoVl|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb3aba9f08194ba4ad9566d6ded80","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_supervisor_contract.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n 554 - `s1_preflight_checker` is implemented as the entry gate for the sector\n 555 - `s1_paths_resolver` is implemented as the canonical path/structure resolver for the sector\n 556 - `script_batch_planner` is implemented as the first batching/planning skill for the sector\n 557 - `scene_director_io_adapter` is implemented as the explicit batch contract bridge to the `scene_director` operator\n-558 - `screenplay_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for batch screenplay outputs\n+558 - `scene_director_output_validator` is now required as the deterministic per-batch validation gate for `scene_director` outputs before merge\n+559 - `screenplay_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for approved batch screenplay outputs\n 559 - `tts_polish_batch_planner` is implemented as the batching/planning layer for `tts_polish`\n 560 - `tts_polish_io_adapter` is implemented as the explicit batch contract bridge to the `tts_polish` operator\n 561 - `tts_polish_merger` is implemented as the deterministic recomposition layer for batch polish outputs\n 562 - `retry_planner` is implemented as the retry decision layer for the supervisor\n     ...","firstChangedLine":558},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774957489596}}
{"type":"message","id":"8976f655","parentId":"1984394d","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:45:14.368Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Feito. Organizei e avancei exactamente na sequência que combinámos.\n\n## O que foi feito\n\n### 1. Reorganização de contracts\nCriei:\n- `docs/contracts/s1/`\n\nE movi para lá:\n- `docs/contracts/s1/s1_supervisor_contract.md`\n- `docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_contract.md`\n\nMantendo o prefixo `s1_`, como combinámos.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Actualização do `s1_scene_director_contract.md`\nAdicionei:\n- validação **por batch** antes de qualquer merge\n- loop de correcção focado só no batch falhado\n- regra de que a política de validação/retry pertence ao supervisor\n- noção de modos:\n  - `generate`\n  - `repair`\n\nSem deixar o `scene_director` virar dono da própria validação.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Actualização do `s1_supervisor_contract.md`\nAdicionei explicitamente:\n- `scene_director_output_validator` como skill agora necessária\n- precondição de que o `screenplay_merger` só recebe batches aprovados\n- regra de que o supervisor **não pode** mergear batch inválido\n- unidade de retry do `scene_director` = **batch**\n- distinção conceptual entre:\n  - structural patch\n  - batch repair\n  - full batch regeneration\n\n---\n\n### 4. Criação do novo contract da validator skill\nCriei:\n- `docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md`\n\nCom:\n- purpose\n- scope\n- out of scope\n- inputs mínimos\n- output shape draft\n- classificações:\n  - `ok`\n  - `structural_patch`\n  - `batch_repair`\n  - `batch_regenerate`\n  - `fatal_contract_error`\n- relação com o supervisor\n- relação com o `scene_director`\n\n---\n\n# Minha leitura\nA arquitectura ficou **bem mais sólida** agora.\n\nEspecialmente porque ficou explícito que:\n- a unidade de controlo é o **batch**\n- a unidade de retry é o **batch**\n- o merge só acontece **depois da aprovação batch a batch**\n- o supervisor mantém a governança\n- o operator continua especialista, não mini-orquestrador\n\n---\n\n# Próximo passo lógico\nAgora eu vejo dois caminhos possíveis, e ambos fazem sentido:\n\n## opção A\nRevisar juntos o novo contract:\n- `s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md`\n\n## opção B\nParar e afiar primeiro uma questão crítica:\n**como distinguir bem `structural_patch` vs `batch_repair` vs `batch_regenerate`**\n\n### Minha recomendação\n**Opção B primeiro.**\n\nPorque essa classificação é o coração da estratégia.  \nSe ela ficar mal definida, o resto da skill fica meio frouxo.\n\nSe quiser, eu já proponho agora uma tabela clara com exemplos de cada classe.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb3b879a08194b7c927aeb69dfae8\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":216,"output":616,"cacheRead":69888,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":70720,"cost":{"input":0.00054,"output":0.00924,"cacheRead":0.017471999999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.027252}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774957490173,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb3b6f4948194aa4ffd6154e59895"}}
{"type":"message","id":"3e5f818e","parentId":"8976f655","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:46:46.214Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:46 GMT-3] blz pode trazer, e ai depois disso criar a skill eu acredito"}],"timestamp":1774957606122}}
{"type":"message","id":"f0a125f5","parentId":"3e5f818e","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:47:21.448Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Perfeito. Vamos afiar essa classificação, porque ela é mesmo o coração do loop.\n\n# Objectivo da classificação\nA classificação não existe para “descrever erro bonito”.  \nEla existe para o supervisor decidir **qual a menor intervenção confiável** para resolver o batch.\n\nOu seja:\n\n- corrigir localmente?\n- pedir repair semântico do batch?\n- regenerar o batch inteiro?\n- abortar porque o artefacto está quebrado demais?\n\n---\n\n# Minha proposta de classificação\n\n## 1. `structural_patch`\n### Quando usar\nQuando o output está **essencialmente correcto**, e o problema é **local, mecânico e de baixo risco**, sem exigir reinterpretação real da segmentação.\n\n### Tipo de erro típico\n- `scene_local_id` fora de sequência\n- campo obrigatório faltando, mas claramente inferível/recuperável\n- `estimated_scene_word_count` inconsistente\n- `operator` ou `batch_id` errado/incompleto\n- pequena inconsistência estrutural que não afecta a lógica narrativa nem a divisão real das cenas\n\n### Intuição\nO batch continua confiável como estrutura de cenas.  \nO problema é mais “formato / housekeeping” do que “pensamento errado”.\n\n### Acção recomendada do supervisor\n- pode pedir **repair estruturado**\n- ou eventualmente permitir patch determinístico por skill, **se isso for absolutamente seguro**\n- não precisa regenerar o batch inteiro\n\n### Exemplo\n- cenas estão boas\n- textos estão certos\n- sem overlap\n- cobertura completa\n- mas `scene_local_id` veio:\n  - `scene_01`\n  - `scene_03`\n  - `scene_02`\n\nIsto não exige reinterpretação narrativa. Exige arrumar estrutura.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `batch_repair`\n### Quando usar\nQuando o batch tem valor aproveitável, mas há problemas que exigem o `scene_director` **revisar o próprio output com feedback específico**.\n\n### Tipo de erro típico\n- pequena sobreposição localizada entre duas cenas\n- pequeno gap de cobertura\n- `narration_original` incorrecto em 1 cena isolada\n- uma cena mal delimitada, mas o resto do batch está bom\n- summary ou narrative function incoerente em pontos específicos, sem colapsar o batch todo\n\n### Intuição\nO batch não está “podre”.  \nMas também não é só um problema cosmético.  \nPrecisa de **revisão localizada orientada**, não de rebuild cego.\n\n### Acção recomendada do supervisor\n- reinvocar `scene_director` em modo **repair**\n- enviar:\n  - batch source\n  - output anterior\n  - erros específicos\n  - instruções de correcção\n\n### Exemplo\n- batch 6 tem 5 cenas\n- tudo está bom excepto:\n  - overlap entre scene_02 e scene_03\n  - words 188–214 ficaram sem cobertura\n- isso pode exigir reabrir a segmentação local\n- mas não necessariamente destruir o batch inteiro\n\n---\n\n## 3. `batch_regenerate`\n### Quando usar\nQuando a integridade do batch está comprometida o suficiente para que tentar “remendar” seja menos confiável do que gerar de novo com constraints melhores.\n\n### Tipo de erro típico\n- múltiplos overlaps ao longo do batch\n- cobertura quebrada em vários pontos\n- várias cenas com `narration_original` errado\n- segmentação global do batch claramente ruim\n- cena boundaries caóticos\n- output semanticamente desalinhado do trecho fonte\n- demasiados erros combinados para confiar numa repair incremental\n\n### Intuição\nO batch perdeu confiabilidade como unidade.  \nMesmo que dê para salvar partes, o risco de inconsistência oculta é alto.\n\n### Acção recomendada do supervisor\n- pedir **regeneração do batch**\n- mantendo o mesmo batch source\n- com feedback explícito sobre o que falhou\n\n### Exemplo\n- batch com 6 cenas\n- 3 têm overlap\n- 2 têm gaps\n- 2 têm narration drift\n- ids fora de ordem\n- contagens incoerentes\n\nAqui repair vira gambiarra. Melhor regenerar.\n\n---\n\n## 4. `fatal_contract_error`\n### Quando usar\nQuando o artefacto nem entra direito no loop normal.\n\n### Tipo de erro típico\n- JSON inválido / unreadable\n- falta `scenes`\n- top-level shape errado\n- campos-base ausentes de forma que o validator nem consegue comparar direito\n- payload/output tão quebrado que não dá para classificar bem o conteúdo\n\n### Intuição\nAntes de discutir qualidade do batch, o contract básico já falhou.\n\n### Acção recomendada do supervisor\n- normalmente **não mergear**\n- decidir entre:\n  - regenerate imediato\n  - abortar step\n  - marcar erro estrutural mais grave\n\n### Exemplo\n- ficheiro vazio\n- JSON quebrado\n- `scenes` vem string em vez de array\n- output não corresponde ao contract esperado\n\n---\n\n# Heurística prática para o supervisor\nA forma simples de decidir:\n\n## `structural_patch`\n**A cena está certa, o invólucro está torto.**\n\n## `batch_repair`\n**O batch está em grande parte certo, mas precisa de revisão localizada.**\n\n## `batch_regenerate`\n**Já não dá para confiar no batch como unidade; melhor refazer.**\n\n## `fatal_contract_error`\n**Nem o contract básico foi cumprido.**\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação operacional\nEu **não** deixaria `structural_patch` significar “a skill corrige sozinha” por default.\n\nMelhor pensar assim:\n\n- `structural_patch` = classe de erro de baixo risco\n- depois decidimos se:\n  - supervisor manda para `scene_director(repair)`, ou\n  - alguma patch skill determinística pode corrigir certos casos no futuro\n\nPorque se abrirmos patch automático cedo demais, podemos introduzir correcções silenciosas demais.\n\n---\n\n# Tabela mental rápida\n\n## `structural_patch`\n- problema local\n- baixo risco\n- sem mexer no raciocínio narrativo\n\n## `batch_repair`\n- problema real\n- localizado\n- batch ainda confiável em grande parte\n\n## `batch_regenerate`\n- problema amplo\n- batch perdeu integridade\n\n## `fatal_contract_error`\n- artefacto quebrado na base\n\n---\n\n# Minha opinião honesta\nA distinção mais importante mesmo é esta:\n\n### `batch_repair` vs `batch_regenerate`\n\nPorque `structural_patch` e `fatal_contract_error` são mais fáceis de detectar.\n\nO centro da arquitectura está em saber:\n- quando vale a pena revisar o output existente\n- e quando é melhor mandar refazer aquele batch\n\n---\n\n## Minha sugestão de próximo passo\nAntes de criar a skill, eu sugiro fixarmos **regras de decisão mínimas**, por exemplo:\n\n- 1 erro estrutural isolado → `structural_patch`\n- 1–2 erros localizados de coverage/overlap/mismatch → `batch_repair`\n- múltiplos erros de coverage/overlap/mismatch no mesmo batch → `batch_regenerate`\n- JSON ilegível / sem shape base → `fatal_contract_error`\n\nNão precisa ser perfeito agora, mas precisa existir um critério inicial.\n\nSe quiser, eu posso já transformar isso numa **primeira policy v1** pronta para entrar no contract da validator skill e depois seguimos para desenhar a skill em si.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb42ed6fc819491ce6b31ce7dcf9b\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":70792,"output":1568,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":72360,"cost":{"input":0.17698000000000003,"output":0.02352,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.2005}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774957607153,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb42a719881949696c26590795906"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1905df73","parentId":"f0a125f5","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:48:40.031Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 08:48 GMT-3] Perfeito Tobias, pode fazer."}],"timestamp":1774957719951}}
{"type":"message","id":"8f20f32c","parentId":"1905df73","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:48:55.027Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_gvQqUxBbEyooVVEKDzQweNTL|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb49cd774819492c1ee3cd04446f1","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md","oldText":"## Failure classification intent\n\n### `structural_patch`\nUse when the problem is narrow and local, for example:\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\n- malformed local id formatting/sequencing\n- small metadata inconsistency\n\n### `batch_repair`\nUse when the batch output should be revised with structured feedback, but the batch remains locally salvageable.\n\n### `batch_regenerate`\nUse when the current batch output is too structurally or textually compromised to trust targeted repair, for example:\n- major overlap\n- major missing coverage\n- multiple narration/source mismatches\n- broken scene segmentation across the batch\n\n### `fatal_contract_error`\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for normal repair flow, for example:\n- unreadable JSON\n- missing top-level required structure\n- missing source comparability conditions\n","newText":"## Failure classification intent\n\n### `structural_patch`\nUse when the problem is narrow, local, and low-risk, while the batch remains otherwise trustworthy as a scene structure artifact.\n\nTypical examples:\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\n- malformed local id formatting/sequencing\n- small metadata inconsistency\n- wrong/inconsistent `estimated_scene_word_count`\n- top-level bookkeeping issue that does not require rethinking scene segmentation\n\nDecision intuition:\n- the scenes are basically right\n- the wrapper/structure is wrong\n- no meaningful narrative reinterpretation is needed\n\n### `batch_repair`\nUse when the batch output should be revised with structured feedback, but the batch remains locally salvageable and still contains meaningful reusable work.\n\nTypical examples:\n- localized overlap between adjacent scenes\n- small missing coverage gap\n- one scene with `narration_original` mismatch\n- one scene boundary that needs correction while the rest of the batch remains sound\n\nDecision intuition:\n- the batch is not clean enough to approve\n- the batch is still good enough to revise rather than rebuild from scratch\n- supervisor should target the existing output with explicit repair feedback\n\n### `batch_regenerate`\nUse when the current batch output is too structurally or textually compromised to trust targeted repair.\n\nTypical examples:\n- multiple overlaps across the batch\n- multiple missing coverage regions\n- multiple narration/source mismatches\n- broken scene segmentation across the batch\n- many combined structural/fidelity failures that undermine trust in the artifact as a whole\n\nDecision intuition:\n- the batch has lost integrity as a unit\n- patching/revising is riskier than regenerating\n- supervisor should request a new generation for that batch with explicit failure feedback\n\n### `fatal_contract_error`\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for the normal repair flow.\n\nTypical examples:\n- unreadable JSON\n- missing top-level required structure\n- missing source comparability conditions\n- `scenes` missing or unusable as a sequence\n\nDecision intuition:\n- the artifact does not satisfy the basic contract needed for normal validation and retry handling\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md\",\"oldText\":\"## Failure classification intent\\n\\n### `structural_patch`\\nUse when the problem is narrow and local, for example:\\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\\n- malformed local id formatting/sequencing\\n- small metadata inconsistency\\n\\n### `batch_repair`\\nUse when the batch output should be revised with structured feedback, but the batch remains locally salvageable.\\n\\n### `batch_regenerate`\\nUse when the current batch output is too structurally or textually compromised to trust targeted repair, for example:\\n- major overlap\\n- major missing coverage\\n- multiple narration/source mismatches\\n- broken scene segmentation across the batch\\n\\n### `fatal_contract_error`\\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for normal repair flow, for example:\\n- unreadable JSON\\n- missing top-level required structure\\n- missing source comparability conditions\\n\",\"newText\":\"## Failure classification intent\\n\\n### `structural_patch`\\nUse when the problem is narrow, local, and low-risk, while the batch remains otherwise trustworthy as a scene structure artifact.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\\n- malformed local id formatting/sequencing\\n- small metadata inconsistency\\n- wrong/inconsistent `estimated_scene_word_count`\\n- top-level bookkeeping issue that does not require rethinking scene segmentation\\n\\nDecision intuition:\\n- the scenes are basically right\\n- the wrapper/structure is wrong\\n- no meaningful narrative reinterpretation is needed\\n\\n### `batch_repair`\\nUse when the batch output should be revised with structured feedback, but the batch remains locally salvageable and still contains meaningful reusable work.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- localized overlap between adjacent scenes\\n- small missing coverage gap\\n- one scene with `narration_original` mismatch\\n- one scene boundary that needs correction while the rest of the batch remains sound\\n\\nDecision intuition:\\n- the batch is not clean enough to approve\\n- the batch is still good enough to revise rather than rebuild from scratch\\n- supervisor should target the existing output with explicit repair feedback\\n\\n### `batch_regenerate`\\nUse when the current batch output is too structurally or textually compromised to trust targeted repair.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- multiple overlaps across the batch\\n- multiple missing coverage regions\\n- multiple narration/source mismatches\\n- broken scene segmentation across the batch\\n- many combined structural/fidelity failures that undermine trust in the artifact as a whole\\n\\nDecision intuition:\\n- the batch has lost integrity as a unit\\n- patching/revising is riskier than regenerating\\n- supervisor should request a new generation for that batch with explicit failure feedback\\n\\n### `fatal_contract_error`\\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for the normal repair flow.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- unreadable JSON\\n- missing top-level required structure\\n- missing source comparability conditions\\n- `scenes` missing or unusable as a sequence\\n\\nDecision intuition:\\n- the artifact does not satisfy the basic contract needed for normal validation and retry handling\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":233,"output":673,"cacheRead":72192,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73098,"cost":{"input":0.0005825,"output":0.010095,"cacheRead":0.018047999999999998,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.028725499999999998}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774957721093,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb49bed348194a2d469d04ee93e57"}}
{"type":"message","id":"1a584950","parentId":"8f20f32c","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:48:55.589Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_gvQqUxBbEyooVVEKDzQweNTL|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb49cd774819492c1ee3cd04446f1","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  95 \n  96 ## Failure classification intent\n  97 \n  98 ### `structural_patch`\n- 99 Use when the problem is narrow and local, for example:\n+ 99 Use when the problem is narrow, local, and low-risk, while the batch remains otherwise trustworthy as a scene structure artifact.\n+100 \n+101 Typical examples:\n 100 - missing field with otherwise stable structure\n 101 - malformed local id formatting/sequencing\n 102 - small metadata inconsistency\n+105 - wrong/inconsistent `estimated_scene_word_count`\n+106 - top-level bookkeeping issue that does not require rethinking scene segmentation\n 103 \n+108 Decision intuition:\n+109 - the scenes are basically right\n+110 - the wrapper/structure is wrong\n+111 - no meaningful narrative reinterpretation is needed\n+112 \n 104 ### `batch_repair`\n-105 Use when the batch output should be revised with structured feedback, but the batch remains locally salvageable.\n+114 Use when the batch output should be revised with structured feedback, but the batch remains locally salvageable and still contains meaningful reusable work.\n 106 \n+116 Typical examples:\n+117 - localized overlap between adjacent scenes\n+118 - small missing coverage gap\n+119 - one scene with `narration_original` mismatch\n+120 - one scene boundary that needs correction while the rest of the batch remains sound\n+121 \n+122 Decision intuition:\n+123 - the batch is not clean enough to approve\n+124 - the batch is still good enough to revise rather than rebuild from scratch\n+125 - supervisor should target the existing output with explicit repair feedback\n+126 \n 107 ### `batch_regenerate`\n-108 Use when the current batch output is too structurally or textually compromised to trust targeted repair, for example:\n-109 - major overlap\n-110 - major missing coverage\n+128 Use when the current batch output is too structurally or textually compromised to trust targeted repair.\n+129 \n+130 Typical examples:\n+131 - multiple overlaps across the batch\n+132 - multiple missing coverage regions\n 111 - multiple narration/source mismatches\n 112 - broken scene segmentation across the batch\n+135 - many combined structural/fidelity failures that undermine trust in the artifact as a whole\n 113 \n+137 Decision intuition:\n+138 - the batch has lost integrity as a unit\n+139 - patching/revising is riskier than regenerating\n+140 - supervisor should request a new generation for that batch with explicit failure feedback\n+141 \n 114 ### `fatal_contract_error`\n-115 Use when the artifact is too malformed for normal repair flow, for example:\n+143 Use when the artifact is too malformed for the normal repair flow.\n+144 \n+145 Typical examples:\n 116 - unreadable JSON\n 117 - missing top-level required structure\n 118 - missing source comparability conditions\n+149 - `scenes` missing or unusable as a sequence\n 119 \n+151 Decision intuition:\n+152 - the artifact does not satisfy the basic contract needed for normal validation and retry handling\n+153 \n 120 ---\n 121 \n 122 ## Validation principles\n 123 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":99},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774957735472}}
{"type":"message","id":"02316357","parentId":"1a584950","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:49:01.314Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_MxVOzNdLi3jifKUuXcSR9d9H|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb4ab8a688194b35b269c94f1ac95","name":"edit","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md","oldText":"These are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\n\n---\n\n## Failure classification intent\n","newText":"These are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\n\n### Initial classification policy (v1)\nA practical first-pass policy for the supervisor/validator layer:\n- one isolated low-risk structural issue -> `structural_patch`\n- one or two localized coverage/overlap/text-fidelity issues in an otherwise coherent batch -> `batch_repair`\n- multiple coverage/overlap/text-fidelity issues across the same batch -> `batch_regenerate`\n- unreadable or fundamentally malformed artifact -> `fatal_contract_error`\n\nThis policy is intentionally simple and can be refined once real batch outputs are observed.\n\n---\n\n## Failure classification intent\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md\",\"oldText\":\"These are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Failure classification intent\\n\",\"newText\":\"These are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\\n\\n### Initial classification policy (v1)\\nA practical first-pass policy for the supervisor/validator layer:\\n- one isolated low-risk structural issue -> `structural_patch`\\n- one or two localized coverage/overlap/text-fidelity issues in an otherwise coherent batch -> `batch_repair`\\n- multiple coverage/overlap/text-fidelity issues across the same batch -> `batch_regenerate`\\n- unreadable or fundamentally malformed artifact -> `fatal_contract_error`\\n\\nThis policy is intentionally simple and can be refined once real batch outputs are observed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Failure classification intent\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":180,"output":210,"cacheRead":72960,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73350,"cost":{"input":0.00045000000000000004,"output":0.00315,"cacheRead":0.01824,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.02184}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774957736145,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb4aab8108194b29c34459bd3d051"}}
{"type":"message","id":"3a9f6533","parentId":"02316357","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:49:01.868Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"call_MxVOzNdLi3jifKUuXcSR9d9H|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb4ab8a688194b35b269c94f1ac95","toolName":"edit","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Successfully replaced text in C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md."}],"details":{"diff":"     ...\n  90 - `fatal_contract_error`\n  91 \n  92 These are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\n  93 \n+ 94 ### Initial classification policy (v1)\n+ 95 A practical first-pass policy for the supervisor/validator layer:\n+ 96 - one isolated low-risk structural issue -> `structural_patch`\n+ 97 - one or two localized coverage/overlap/text-fidelity issues in an otherwise coherent batch -> `batch_repair`\n+ 98 - multiple coverage/overlap/text-fidelity issues across the same batch -> `batch_regenerate`\n+ 99 - unreadable or fundamentally malformed artifact -> `fatal_contract_error`\n+100 \n+101 This policy is intentionally simple and can be refined once real batch outputs are observed.\n+102 \n  94 ---\n  95 \n  96 ## Failure classification intent\n  97 \n     ...","firstChangedLine":94},"isError":false,"timestamp":1774957741741}}
{"type":"message","id":"d5b8df1f","parentId":"3a9f6533","timestamp":"2026-03-31T11:49:13.563Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Feito.\n\nAdicionei ao `s1_scene_director_output_validator_contract.md`:\n\n- uma **policy inicial v1 de classificação**\n- definições mais nítidas para:\n  - `structural_patch`\n  - `batch_repair`\n  - `batch_regenerate`\n  - `fatal_contract_error`\n- exemplos típicos\n- a intuição de decisão por trás de cada classe\n\n## O que ficou fixado como policy v1\n- **1 erro estrutural isolado e de baixo risco** → `structural_patch`\n- **1–2 erros localizados de coverage / overlap / fidelidade** → `batch_repair`\n- **múltiplos erros desse tipo no mesmo batch** → `batch_regenerate`\n- **artefacto ilegível ou malformado na base** → `fatal_contract_error`\n\nE deixei explícito que isso é:\n- uma política inicial\n- simples de propósito\n- refinável depois com outputs reais\n\n---\n\n# Próximo passo: criar a skill\nAqui eu acho que faz sentido, sim.\n\n## Minha recomendação de abordagem\nAntes de codar full implementation, eu faria primeiro uma definição curta da skill em termos de:\n\n1. **nome e localização**\n2. **input shape**\n3. **output shape**\n4. **regras determinísticas exactas**\n5. **ordem dos checks**\n6. **o que conta como word span / coverage**\n7. **como comparar `narration_original` com source text**\n\nPorque o maior risco agora não é “esquecer de criar a skill”.  \nÉ criar uma skill sem semântica precisa de:\n- tokenização\n- coverage\n- comparação de texto\n- tolerância vs exact match\n\n---\n\n# Minha proposta\nSe quiser, seguimos assim agora:\n\n## Skill: `scene_director_output_validator`\nE eu te trago em seguida uma proposta objectiva de:\n\n- **onde ela vive**\n- **qual ficheiro teria**\n- **qual a assinatura**\n- **qual a sequência de validações**\n- **quais decisões precisam ser tomadas antes de implementar**\n\nEsse é o passo certo antes de meter a mão no código.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb4b28dd48194a87732e3bbe26317\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":176,"output":454,"cacheRead":73216,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":73846,"cost":{"input":0.00044,"output":0.00681,"cacheRead":0.018304,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.025554}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774957742426,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbb4b12d5081949c16203fe013fae0"}}
