{"type":"message","id":"3dd841c5","parentId":"4c97ff61","timestamp":"2026-03-31T14:41:39.651Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Perfeito. Vou seguir já mais independente e trazer a peça quase fechada.\n\n# `tts_polish` — proposta estruturada\n\n---\n\n# 1. Missão\nJá validada:\n\n**Transformar a narração original de cada cena numa versão optimizada para TTS, preservando integralmente o significado e a informação, enquanto melhora clareza oral, pronúncia, fluidez e legibilidade para voz sintética.**\n\n---\n\n# 2. Responsabilidade central\nMinha proposta refinada:\n\n**Ajustar a formulação oral de pequenas sequências de cenas para TTS, preservando integralmente conteúdo, cobertura e ordem, enquanto melhora a legibilidade oral de cada cena sem alterar a estrutura narrativa recebida.**\n\n## Porque esta formulação está boa\nEla fixa que o `tts_polish`:\n- trabalha em **batches pequenos de cenas**\n- preserva **conteúdo**\n- preserva **cobertura**\n- preserva **ordem**\n- melhora **oralidade**\n- **não mexe na estrutura narrativa**\n\nIsto é importante porque o `tts_polish` não deve redecidir o trabalho do `scene_director`.\n\n---\n\n# 3. Unidade operacional\n## Definição correcta\n- unidade semântica principal: **cena**\n- unidade operacional/orquestracional: **batch pequeno de cenas**\n\n### defaults já definidos no supervisor\n- target: `5` cenas\n- mínimo: `3`\n- máximo: `6`\n- máximo aprox.: `350` palavras por batch\n\n---\n\n# 4. Input do `tts_polish`\n## O que ele deve receber\nPara cada invocação, o `tts_polish` deve receber um **batch ordenado de cenas** já vindas do `screenplay.json`.\n\n### input mínimo\n- run/job context\n- `batch_id` (`tp_###`)\n- lista ordenada de cenas\n- para cada cena:\n  - `scene_id`\n  - `narration_original`\n- regras de polish aplicáveis (`tts_polish_rules`)\n- output path esperado\n\n## O que ele **não** precisa receber\n- script bruto inteiro\n- lógica de batching\n- retry policy\n- validator result previo como regra normal\n- visual planning context\n- asset planning context\n\n---\n\n# 5. Output do `tts_polish`\n## Minha proposta\nCada batch deve devolver um JSON com:\n- `batch_id`\n- `operator`\n- `scenes`\n\n### para cada cena\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\n## Campo opcional\n- `changes`\n\n### Minha recomendação\nNo contract:\n- obrigatórios:\n  - `scene_id`\n  - `narration_original`\n  - `narration_tts`\n- opcional:\n  - `changes`\n\nPorque o activo principal do sector é:\n- original preservado\n- versão TTS optimizada\n\n---\n\n# 6. Boundaries / out of scope\nO `tts_polish` **não deve**:\n\n- alterar meaning\n- adicionar ou remover informação\n- mudar ordem das cenas\n- fundir ou dividir cenas\n- reestruturar narrativa\n- corrigir estrategicamente a divisão de cenas\n- fazer visual planning\n- fazer validação semântica final\n- decidir retry\n- produzir áudio\n- mexer em timestamps\n\n## Formulação importante\nO `tts_polish` **não é writer nem editor narrativo estrutural**.  \nÉ um **normalizador oral controlado**.\n\n---\n\n# 7. O que ele pode alterar legitimamente\nAqui a V3 ajudou muito.\n\nEle pode actuar em coisas como:\n- ortografia\n- acentuação\n- expansão de abreviações\n- ordinais / numerais romanos\n- unidades\n- siglas quando apropriado\n- pequenas escolhas de legibilidade oral\n\n## Mas sempre sob esta regra:\n> só o mínimo necessário para a leitura TTS ficar melhor\n\n---\n\n# 8. Quality bar do `tts_polish`\nUm bom output de `tts_polish` deve:\n\n- soar melhor para TTS do que o original cru\n- preservar a informação integralmente\n- não perder palavras importantes\n- não introduzir palavras indevidas\n- manter a ordem exacta das cenas\n- melhorar leitura oral sem “reescrever a história”\n\n---\n\n# 9. Validator\n## Sim, deve existir\nMinha recomendação é:\n\n### nome\n`tts_polish_output_validator`\n\nou, para ficar alinhado com naming do sector:\n` s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md ` no contract\ne skill correspondente\n\n## Papel da validator\nValidar deterministicamente, por batch de polish:\n- shape do output\n- presença de cenas esperadas\n- ordem das cenas\n- `scene_id` correcto\n- `narration_original` preservado\n- detecção de:\n  - eaten words\n  - unauthorized additions\n  - dangerous drift\n  - scene mismatch\n\n### Ponto importante\nA validação semântica mais crítica continua a acontecer **cena por cena**, mesmo dentro do batch.\n\nOu seja:\n- batch é unidade operacional\n- cena continua a ser unidade fina de comparação\n\n---\n\n# 10. Contracts que o `tts_polish` provavelmente vai precisar\nSeguindo o padrão que usamos no `scene_director`, eu recomendaria:\n\n## primeiro\n`docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_contract.md`\n\n## depois\n`docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\n\nTal como fizemos antes.\n\n---\n\n# 11. Workspace real do agent\nSe seguirmos a convenção que definimos para `scene_director`, minha recomendação seria:\n\n## path\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\`\n\nAcho que esse naming fica perfeito ao lado de:\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- `op_s1_scene_director`\n\n---\n\n# Conclusão\n## O que eu acho que já está suficientemente claro\n- missão\n- responsabilidade central\n- unidade operacional\n- input\n- output\n- boundaries\n- necessidade de validator\n- naming provável do workspace\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação de próxima sequência\nAgora eu faria:\n\n## 1.\ncriar o contract:\n`docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_contract.md`\n\n## 2.\ndepois criar:\n`docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\n\n## 3.\ndepois criar o workspace real:\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\`\n\n---\n\nSe quiser, eu já posso começar pelo passo 1 e criar o `s1_tts_polish_contract.md` com base nesta definição.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbdd0b27e48194bcfb9c23226f6ff2\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":1774,"output":1418,"cacheRead":158080,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":161272,"cost":{"input":0.004435000000000001,"output":0.02127,"cacheRead":0.03952,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.065225}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774968068116,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbdd073d1c819492ef4527627dac87"}}
{"type":"message","id":"ce62cd81","parentId":"3dd841c5","timestamp":"2026-03-31T14:44:53.807Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 11:44 GMT-3] vamos só alinahs melhor o validator ali Tobias que ai vc ja cria tudo de uma vez só. Como que essa skill vai funcionar exatamente? Tipo não tem muito como ela ser em python né precisa de uma interpretaçào pra entender se ta correto a adequação ou não né? Além disso, quem vai utilizar s kill? Provavelmente o supervisor. Ai ele usa a skill e o que acontece depois? Como que ele retorna pro tts polish corrigir só aquilo especirficamente ou algo do tipo"}],"timestamp":1774968293725}}
{"type":"message","id":"7998d4fc","parentId":"ce62cd81","timestamp":"2026-03-31T14:45:40.665Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Boa. Aqui vale mesmo abrandar, porque o validator do `tts_polish` é mais subtil do que o do `scene_director`.\n\nNo `scene_director`, muita coisa era auditável deterministicamente:\n- ids\n- spans\n- overlap\n- coverage\n- fidelidade do trecho\n\nNo `tts_polish`, a pergunta deixa de ser só:\n- “está estruturalmente certo?”\n\ne passa a incluir:\n- “o quanto ele mexeu semanticamente?”\n- “essa alteração é uma melhoria legítima de TTS ou drift indevido?”\n\nAí a arquitectura precisa ser mais pensada.\n\n---\n\n# Resposta curta\n## Sim:\neu acho que o **supervisor** continua a ser quem usa a skill.\n\n## Mas:\no validator do `tts_polish` provavelmente **não deve ser 100% Python determinístico puro** no sentido de julgar sozinho toda adequação.\n\nO mais provável é que ele precise de uma arquitectura em camadas.\n\n---\n\n# O problema central\nPrecisamos separar **duas perguntas diferentes**:\n\n## 1. O output respeitou o contrato básico?\nIsto é mais determinístico:\n- shape certo?\n- mesmas cenas?\n- mesma ordem?\n- `scene_id` correcto?\n- `narration_original` preservado?\n- texto polido não está vazio?\n- houve adição/remoção grosseira?\n\n## 2. A adequação para TTS foi boa/aceitável sem drift?\nIsto já é mais interpretativo:\n- melhorou oralidade?\n- a expansão de abreviação fez sentido?\n- o ordinal foi lido certo?\n- a mudança preserva meaning?\n- houve “embelezamento” indevido?\n\nIsto já não é tão Python-puro.\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação arquitectural\n## Fazer o validator do `tts_polish` em 2 camadas\n\n### Camada A — deterministic guardrail layer\nUma skill Python que detecta:\n- shape inválido\n- ordem inválida\n- cena faltando\n- `scene_id` errado\n- `narration_original` divergente\n- palavras comidas\n- adições suspeitas\n- diferenças quantitativas\n- mismatch entre input/output scene mapping\n\n### Camada B — semantic judgment layer\nUma camada mais interpretativa para casos borderline:\n- mudou, mas ainda está aceitável?\n- melhoria legítima de TTS ou drift semântico?\n- expansão de termo ficou melhor ou pior?\n- alteração está dentro das regras do idioma?\n\nEssa camada pode ser:\n- outro operator leve\n- ou um validator semântico leve\n- só invocado quando necessário\n\n---\n\n# Então a resposta à tua pergunta “não tem muito como ser em python né?”\n## Minha resposta:\n**parcialmente em Python, sim**\n— mas **não totalmente**, se quisermos um sistema bom.\n\n### Python serve muito bem para:\n- garantir integridade\n- detectar drift grosseiro\n- garantir que o batch bate com o input\n- medir diferença\n- detectar palavras comidas/adicionadas\n- detectar cena trocada/faltando\n\n### Python não serve tão bem sozinho para:\n- julgar se uma alteração foi uma boa adequação de TTS\n- distinguir certos casos de:\n  - melhoria legítima\n  - drift subtil\n  - leitura mais natural\n  - decisão linguística aceitável\n\n---\n\n# Então quem usa a skill?\n## O supervisor.\nIsso continua igual ao `scene_director`.\n\nFluxo recomendado:\n\n1. supervisor envia batch para `tts_polish`\n2. `tts_polish` devolve batch polido\n3. supervisor roda validator(s)\n4. validator devolve:\n   - ok / not ok\n   - erros estruturais\n   - sinais de drift\n   - talvez classificação\n5. supervisor decide:\n   - aprovar batch\n   - pedir repair\n   - regenerar batch\n   - escalar para semantic review em casos borderline\n\n---\n\n# Como o supervisor retorna pro `tts_polish` corrigir?\nAqui eu manteria a mesma filosofia que definimos para o `scene_director`:\n\n## o supervisor devolve feedback estruturado sobre o batch\nAlgo tipo:\n\n- batch `tp_004`\n- cenas afectadas:\n  - `scene_012`\n  - `scene_013`\n- problemas encontrados:\n  - palavra removida\n  - adição não autorizada\n  - mudança potencial de meaning\n  - reordenação indevida\n- instrução:\n  - reparar só as cenas afectadas\n  - manter as outras intactas\n\n---\n\n# A nuance importante\nNo `tts_polish`, eu acho que o correction loop pode ser ainda mais granular.\n\n## No `scene_director`\na unidade natural era o batch inteiro, porque segmentação local afecta várias cenas.\n\n## No `tts_polish`\nmuitas vezes o erro está em **1 ou 2 cenas dentro do batch**.\n\nEntão eu acho plausível que:\n- o batch seja a unidade de dispatch\n- mas a unidade de repair seja **subset de cenas dentro do batch**\n\nIsto é uma diferença importante.\n\n---\n\n# Minha proposta concreta de arquitectura para o validator do `tts_polish`\n\n## Camada 1 — `tts_polish_output_validator` (Python determinístico)\nValida por batch:\n- top-level shape\n- batch_id\n- cenas presentes\n- ordem preservada\n- `scene_id` correspondem ao input\n- `narration_original` preservado\n- palavras removidas\n- palavras adicionadas\n- tamanho de alteração\n- mudanças suspeitas\n\n### Output possível\n- `ok`\n- `structural_patch`\n- `scene_subset_repair`\n- `batch_regenerate`\n- `needs_semantic_review`\n- `fatal_contract_error`\n\n---\n\n## Camada 2 — semantic reviewer opcional\nSó entra se a camada 1 disser:\n- há mudança relevante\n- não dá para classificar com segurança só por heurística\n\nExemplos:\n- expansão de termo alterou nuance?\n- correção ortográfica é legítima ou trocou entidade?\n- mudança parece pequena em tokens mas pode ter alterado meaning\n\n---\n\n# O que acontece depois\n## cenário A — erro estrutural / drift claro\nSupervisor pede repair directamente ao `tts_polish`\n\nExemplo:\n- `scene_012` perdeu uma palavra\n- `scene_013` adicionou termo novo\n→ repair dessas cenas\n\n## cenário B — borderline\nSupervisor envia para semantic review leve\ne depois decide:\n- approve\n- repair\n- regenerate subset/batch\n\n---\n\n# Minha opinião honesta\nSe tentarmos fazer o validator do `tts_polish` como “só Python” desde o início, o risco é:\n- falso positivo demais\nou\n- confiança demais em regra cega\n\nMas se fizermos uma arquitectura em camadas, fica muito melhor.\n\n---\n\n# Formulação simples da peça\n## Quem usa?\n- **supervisor**\n\n## O que faz primeiro?\n- roda validator determinístico\n\n## Se falha claro?\n- pede repair ao `tts_polish`\n\n## Se fica ambíguo?\n- manda para semantic review leve\n\n## O que o `tts_polish` corrige?\n- idealmente só **as cenas afectadas dentro do batch**, não o batch inteiro sempre\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação prática\nAntes de criar os contracts do `tts_polish`, eu fecharia contigo estas 3 decisões:\n\n## 1.\nO validator do `tts_polish` vai ser:\n- só Python\nou\n- Python + semantic review opcional?\n\n### Minha recomendação:\n**Python + semantic review opcional**\n\n## 2.\nA unidade de repair deve ser:\n- batch inteiro\nou\n- subset de cenas dentro do batch?\n\n### Minha recomendação:\n**subset de cenas dentro do batch**, quando possível\n\n## 3.\nQueremos desde já que o supervisor tenha uma classificação tipo:\n- `scene_subset_repair`\n- `batch_regenerate`\n- `needs_semantic_review`\n\n### Minha recomendação:\n**sim**\n\n---\n\nSe quiser, eu já transformo isso numa proposta bem fechada de como funcionaria o **loop exacto** do `tts_polish` do início ao fim.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbddf0b7448194a444f11175ec4515\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":145939,"output":1692,"cacheRead":14464,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":162095,"cost":{"input":0.36484750000000005,"output":0.02538,"cacheRead":0.003616,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.39384350000000007}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774968295065,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbddeab02c8194a1b3200403732dcb"}}
{"type":"message","id":"dee13dee","parentId":"7998d4fc","timestamp":"2026-03-31T14:52:02.088Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 11:51 GMT-3] Minha recomendação:\nPython + semantic review opcional > Concordo. \n\nMinha recomendação:\nsubset de cenas dentro do batch, quando possível > Concordo considerando que claro podem ter mais de uma cena em um mesmo batch que precise de correçào\n\n\nQueremos desde já que o supervisor tenha uma classificação tipo:\n\nscene_subset_repair\nbatch_regenerate\nneeds_semantic_review\nMinha recomendação:\nsim > Conrodo"}],"timestamp":1774968722006}}
{"type":"message","id":"b81e4d41","parentId":"dee13dee","timestamp":"2026-03-31T14:52:44.382Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Perfeito. Então agora sim temos a espinha dorsal do validator do `tts_polish`.\n\nVou consolidar isso de forma clara.\n\n# Decisões fechadas para o `tts_polish`\n## 1. Arquitetura do validator\n**Python + semantic review opcional**\n\n## 2. Unidade de repair\n**subset de cenas dentro do batch, quando possível**\n\n## 3. Classificações desejadas\nSim, o supervisor deve poder receber classes como:\n- `scene_subset_repair`\n- `batch_regenerate`\n- `needs_semantic_review`\n\n---\n\n# Como eu desenharia o loop exacto do `tts_polish`\n\n## Visão geral\n1. supervisor prepara batch `tp_###`\n2. `tts_polish` devolve batch polido\n3. supervisor roda validator determinístico Python\n4. se necessário, supervisor roda semantic review opcional\n5. supervisor decide:\n   - aprovar batch\n   - repair subset de cenas\n   - regenerar batch\n   - abortar / escalar\n\n---\n\n# Camada 1 — validator determinístico Python\n## O que ele valida\n### Estrutura\n- output legível\n- shape correcto\n- `batch_id`\n- `scenes`\n- cenas esperadas presentes\n\n### Mapeamento\n- `scene_id` bate com input\n- ordem preservada\n- nenhuma cena sumiu\n- nenhuma cena extra apareceu\n\n### Fidelidade hard\n- `narration_original` preservado no output\n- comparação original vs polished por cena\n- detectar:\n  - palavras comidas\n  - palavras adicionadas\n  - trocas suspeitas\n  - diferenças quantitativas muito grandes\n\n### Regras mecânicas\n- `narration_tts` não vazio\n- campos obrigatórios presentes\n- batch output coerente\n\n---\n\n# Output da camada Python\n## Classificações possíveis\n### `ok`\nNenhum problema relevante\n\n### `structural_patch`\nProblema estrutural local de baixo risco\n\n### `scene_subset_repair`\nHá problemas claros em algumas cenas específicas do batch\n\n### `batch_regenerate`\nO batch inteiro está comprometido o suficiente para não valer repair granular\n\n### `needs_semantic_review`\nA camada Python detectou alterações relevantes, mas não consegue decidir sozinha se são adequação legítima ou drift indevido\n\n### `fatal_contract_error`\nOutput quebrado na base\n\n---\n\n# Quando a Python layer mandaria para semantic review?\nExemplos bons:\n\n- houve mudanças substanciais, mas sem deletions óbvias\n- mudança de formulação parece grande demais\n- expansão de termo pode ser legítima ou pode ter alterado nuance\n- correção ortográfica pode ter mexido em nome próprio / entidade\n- números / siglas / abreviações foram alterados e a heurística não tem confiança suficiente\n\n---\n\n# Camada 2 — semantic review opcional\n## Quem faz?\nAinda não precisamos decidir implementação exacta agora, mas arquitecturalmente seria:\n- um reviewer leve\n- provavelmente LLM\n- invocado só em casos borderline\n\n## O que julga?\n- a alteração manteve meaning?\n- a alteração foi legítima para TTS?\n- a alteração respeitou as regras do idioma/canal?\n- houve drift indevido?\n- quais cenas precisam repair?\n\n---\n\n# O que o supervisor faz depois\n## Cenário A — `ok`\n- batch aprovado\n- segue para merge\n\n## Cenário B — `structural_patch`\n- se seguro, patch local\n- ou reenviar subset pequeno ao `tts_polish`\n\n## Cenário C — `scene_subset_repair`\n- supervisor reenviaria ao `tts_polish` **só as cenas afectadas**\n- com feedback estruturado\n\n## Cenário D — `batch_regenerate`\n- supervisor pede novo batch inteiro\n\n## Cenário E — `needs_semantic_review`\n- supervisor chama semantic reviewer\n- reviewer devolve julgamento\n- supervisor decide repair subset / approve / regenerate\n\n## Cenário F — `fatal_contract_error`\n- não mergeia\n- normalmente falha forte / regenerate / abort dependendo do caso\n\n---\n\n# Como o feedback de repair deveria ser enviado ao `tts_polish`\nMinha recomendação:\n\n## Em vez de “refaz o batch”\no supervisor envia algo como:\n\n- `batch_id`: `tp_004`\n- `mode`: `repair`\n- `affected_scenes`:\n  - `scene_012`\n  - `scene_013`\n- `issues`:\n  - `scene_012`: removed word(s)\n  - `scene_013`: unauthorized addition\n- `instructions`:\n  - repair only the affected scenes\n  - preserve all other scenes unchanged\n  - keep meaning and information exactly intact\n\nIsso é muito melhor do que retry cego.\n\n---\n\n# Diferença importante para o `scene_director`\n## `scene_director`\n- retry natural por batch\n- repair granular mais difícil\n- segmentação pode contaminar várias cenas\n\n## `tts_polish`\n- retry granular por subset de cenas faz muito mais sentido\n- porque cada cena é semanticamente mais isolada\n- o batch aqui é sobretudo unidade de eficiência/orquestração\n\nEssa distinção é muito boa e importante.\n\n---\n\n# Minha proposta de nomenclatura\n## Contract do operator\n`docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_contract.md`\n\n## Contract do validator\n`docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\n\n## Skill Python\n`runtime/s1/supervisor_skills/tts_polish_output_validator.py`\n\n## Reviewer semântico opcional\nmais tarde podemos decidir se vira:\n- operator específico\n- skill híbrida\n- reviewer auxiliar do supervisor\n\nAinda não precisamos congelar isso hoje.\n\n---\n\n# Minha leitura\nAgora sim o `tts_polish` já tem uma base suficientemente madura para eu criar os contracts directamente sem ficar a inventar depois.\n\n## O que já está maduro o suficiente\n- missão\n- responsabilidade central\n- unidade operacional\n- input\n- output\n- boundaries\n- arquitectura do validator\n- classificação do loop\n- lógica de repair subset\n\n---\n\n# Próximo passo que eu recomendo\nAgora dá para eu **criar de uma vez**:\n1. `s1_tts_polish_contract.md`\n2. `s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\n3. e se tu quiseres, já em seguida criar o workspace real:\n   - `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\`\n\nSe quiser, eu sigo já nessa sequência.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbdf9dac148194bd9ad4210b03263f\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":156971,"output":1375,"cacheRead":4608,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":162954,"cost":{"input":0.39242750000000004,"output":0.020625,"cacheRead":0.001152,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.41420450000000003}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774968723063,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbdf9723008194aa4939429d1eab38"}}
{"type":"message","id":"da7b3796","parentId":"b81e4d41","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:09:29.221Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 12:09 GMT-3] Show de bola Tobias pode avançar sim"}],"timestamp":1774969769139}}
{"type":"message","id":"875a7553","parentId":"da7b3796","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:11:12.730Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe3b169008194be919e62e6a88b30\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_7W9nQxgmDLhBUjsk1DnLK4jW|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe4126900819480844da6be4c8d0c","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_contract.md","content":"# S1 TTS Polish Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `tts_polish` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `tts_polish` operator is responsible for transforming original scene narration into a version optimized for Text-to-Speech while preserving meaning, information, coverage, and scene order.\n\nIts job is not to rewrite the story, but to apply only the minimum necessary oral/reading adjustments so the narration sounds better in synthetic voice output.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `tts_polish` is:\n\n> Adjust the oral formulation of small ordered batches of scenes for TTS, preserving content, coverage, and scene order while improving pronunciation-readiness, readability, and speech naturalness.\n\nThis means `tts_polish` is a controlled oral-normalization operator, not a free narrative rewriter.\n\n---\n\n## Position inside S1\n\nWithin S1, `tts_polish` operates after the canonical `screenplay.json` exists and before scene bible construction.\n\nIts output is the TTS-optimized narration layer that will later be:\n- validated\n- merged into canonical `tts_polished.json`\n- consumed by downstream audio generation and scene bible construction\n\n`tts_polish` does not own sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\n\n---\n\n## Batch execution model\n\n`tts_polish` operates on small ordered batches of scenes rather than on the full screenplay at once.\n\nInstead:\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `tts_polish_batch_planner` to group scenes into manageable polish batches\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`tp_001`, `tp_002`, ...)\n- each batch preserves screenplay scene order\n- the supervisor uses `tts_polish_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\n- `tts_polish` operates on one polish batch at a time\n- downstream deterministic logic merges approved batch outputs into canonical `tts_polished.json`\n\n### Recommended v1 defaults\n- target scenes per batch: `5`\n- minimum scenes per batch: `3`\n- maximum scenes per batch: `6`\n- maximum words per batch: `350`\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nFor each invocation, `tts_polish` should receive a supervisor-prepared polish batch payload.\n\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity (`tp_###`)\n- ordered batch scenes\n- for each scene: `scene_id` and `narration_original`\n- language / channel context relevant to polish behavior\n- `tts_polish_rules` injected from channel config\n- explicit output path for the batch result\n\nThe operator should receive enough context to polish the assigned scenes correctly, but should not be overloaded with unrelated upstream/downstream concerns.\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`tts_polish` should **not** be responsible for:\n- re-structuring the narrative\n- changing scene order\n- merging or splitting scenes\n- batching logic\n- retry policy\n- semantic validation of its own output\n- visual planning\n- audio generation\n- timestamps or alignment\n\nIt also should not drift into stylistic rewriting beyond what is necessary for TTS readiness.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\n- preparing the polish batch payload\n- deciding when `tts_polish` is called\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\n- validating batch outputs before merge\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\n- deciding whether failures should trigger subset repair, batch regeneration, semantic review, or abort\n\n`tts_polish` is responsible for producing the batch-level TTS-polished output expected by the supervisor contract.\n\n### Validation and correction loop\n- each `tts_polish` batch output is a separately validatable unit\n- semantic comparison remains scene-sensitive inside the batch\n- if one subset of scenes fails, the supervisor should prefer targeted repair of affected scenes when possible\n- validation policy belongs to the supervisor and its deterministic/semantic review layers, not to `tts_polish`\n- `tts_polish` may be reinvoked with structured correction feedback for only the affected scenes in the batch\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nFor each batch, `tts_polish` should write one batch-level JSON result containing:\n- batch identity/context\n- ordered batch scenes\n- no global merge responsibility\n\n### Batch-level structure (draft)\n- `batch_id`\n- `operator`\n- `scenes`\n\n### Required scene fields\nEach scene produced by `tts_polish` should contain:\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\n### Optional scene fields\n- `changes`\n\n### Output principles\n- scene order must be preserved exactly\n- `scene_id` mapping must be preserved exactly\n- `narration_original` must remain the original scene narration\n- `narration_tts` may improve oral readability, but must not alter meaning or information\n- the output should preserve scene granularity and not collapse scenes together\n- global merge of polish batches is not the responsibility of `tts_polish`\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good `tts_polish` output should:\n- sound better for TTS than the original raw narration\n- preserve meaning and information fully\n- avoid eating words or adding unauthorized content\n- preserve scene order and scene identity exactly\n- make only necessary oral/reading adjustments\n- remain narrower than broad narrative rewriting\n\nLikely high-priority failure modes to guard against:\n- eaten words\n- unauthorized additions\n- meaning drift\n- scene mismatch inside batch output\n- reordered scene outputs\n- malformed or incomplete scene objects\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the mission of `tts_polish`\n- its central responsibility\n- its position inside S1\n- its small-batch execution model\n- the current draft of its input/output contracts\n- the expected targeted-repair behavior for affected scene subsets\n\nThe next step is to formalize the output validator contract and then define the real OpenClaw workspace for the operator.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 TTS Polish Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and file contract of the `tts_polish` operator inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `tts_polish` operator is responsible for transforming original scene narration into a version optimized for Text-to-Speech while preserving meaning, information, coverage, and scene order.\\n\\nIts job is not to rewrite the story, but to apply only the minimum necessary oral/reading adjustments so the narration sounds better in synthetic voice output.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Core responsibility\\n\\nThe central responsibility of `tts_polish` is:\\n\\n> Adjust the oral formulation of small ordered batches of scenes for TTS, preserving content, coverage, and scene order while improving pronunciation-readiness, readability, and speech naturalness.\\n\\nThis means `tts_polish` is a controlled oral-normalization operator, not a free narrative rewriter.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Position inside S1\\n\\nWithin S1, `tts_polish` operates after the canonical `screenplay.json` exists and before scene bible construction.\\n\\nIts output is the TTS-optimized narration layer that will later be:\\n- validated\\n- merged into canonical `tts_polished.json`\\n- consumed by downstream audio generation and scene bible construction\\n\\n`tts_polish` does not own sector flow. It operates under S1 Supervisor coordination and explicit file contracts.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Batch execution model\\n\\n`tts_polish` operates on small ordered batches of scenes rather than on the full screenplay at once.\\n\\nInstead:\\n- the S1 Supervisor uses `tts_polish_batch_planner` to group scenes into manageable polish batches\\n- batches are emitted in stable order (`tp_001`, `tp_002`, ...)\\n- each batch preserves screenplay scene order\\n- the supervisor uses `tts_polish_io_adapter` to prepare an explicit payload for each batch\\n- `tts_polish` operates on one polish batch at a time\\n- downstream deterministic logic merges approved batch outputs into canonical `tts_polished.json`\\n\\n### Recommended v1 defaults\\n- target scenes per batch: `5`\\n- minimum scenes per batch: `3`\\n- maximum scenes per batch: `6`\\n- maximum words per batch: `350`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Input contract (current draft)\\n\\nFor each invocation, `tts_polish` should receive a supervisor-prepared polish batch payload.\\n\\nThe payload should include, at minimum:\\n- run/job context\\n- batch identity (`tp_###`)\\n- ordered batch scenes\\n- for each scene: `scene_id` and `narration_original`\\n- language / channel context relevant to polish behavior\\n- `tts_polish_rules` injected from channel config\\n- explicit output path for the batch result\\n\\nThe operator should receive enough context to polish the assigned scenes correctly, but should not be overloaded with unrelated upstream/downstream concerns.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Boundaries / out of scope\\n\\n`tts_polish` should **not** be responsible for:\\n- re-structuring the narrative\\n- changing scene order\\n- merging or splitting scenes\\n- batching logic\\n- retry policy\\n- semantic validation of its own output\\n- visual planning\\n- audio generation\\n- timestamps or alignment\\n\\nIt also should not drift into stylistic rewriting beyond what is necessary for TTS readiness.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship with S1 Supervisor\\n\\nThe S1 Supervisor is responsible for:\\n- preparing the polish batch payload\\n- deciding when `tts_polish` is called\\n- scheduling batches with controlled parallelism\\n- validating batch outputs before merge\\n- deciding retry/fail/continue behavior\\n- deciding whether failures should trigger subset repair, batch regeneration, semantic review, or abort\\n\\n`tts_polish` is responsible for producing the batch-level TTS-polished output expected by the supervisor contract.\\n\\n### Validation and correction loop\\n- each `tts_polish` batch output is a separately validatable unit\\n- semantic comparison remains scene-sensitive inside the batch\\n- if one subset of scenes fails, the supervisor should prefer targeted repair of affected scenes when possible\\n- validation policy belongs to the supervisor and its deterministic/semantic review layers, not to `tts_polish`\\n- `tts_polish` may be reinvoked with structured correction feedback for only the affected scenes in the batch\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output contract\\n\\nFor each batch, `tts_polish` should write one batch-level JSON result containing:\\n- batch identity/context\\n- ordered batch scenes\\n- no global merge responsibility\\n\\n### Batch-level structure (draft)\\n- `batch_id`\\n- `operator`\\n- `scenes`\\n\\n### Required scene fields\\nEach scene produced by `tts_polish` should contain:\\n- `scene_id`\\n- `narration_original`\\n- `narration_tts`\\n\\n### Optional scene fields\\n- `changes`\\n\\n### Output principles\\n- scene order must be preserved exactly\\n- `scene_id` mapping must be preserved exactly\\n- `narration_original` must remain the original scene narration\\n- `narration_tts` may improve oral readability, but must not alter meaning or information\\n- the output should preserve scene granularity and not collapse scenes together\\n- global merge of polish batches is not the responsibility of `tts_polish`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Quality bar\\n\\nA good `tts_polish` output should:\\n- sound better for TTS than the original raw narration\\n- preserve meaning and information fully\\n- avoid eating words or adding unauthorized content\\n- preserve scene order and scene identity exactly\\n- make only necessary oral/reading adjustments\\n- remain narrower than broad narrative rewriting\\n\\nLikely high-priority failure modes to guard against:\\n- eaten words\\n- unauthorized additions\\n- meaning drift\\n- scene mismatch inside batch output\\n- reordered scene outputs\\n- malformed or incomplete scene objects\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current status\\n\\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\\n- the mission of `tts_polish`\\n- its central responsibility\\n- its position inside S1\\n- its small-batch execution model\\n- the current draft of its input/output contracts\\n- the expected targeted-repair behavior for affected scene subsets\\n\\nThe next step is to formalize the output validator contract and then define the real OpenClaw workspace for the operator.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_rChvvhG5gGn4vnd56rlkOO3y|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe41269188194bcc52b39ecd34bdb","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md","content":"# S1 TTS Polish Output Validator Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the validation contract for per-batch `tts_polish` outputs inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\n`tts_polish_output_validator` validates one `tts_polish` batch output before that batch is allowed into the canonical `tts_polished.json` merge flow.\n\nIts job is to ensure that each polish batch result is structurally sound, preserves scene identity/order, preserves original narration reference, and does not introduce unacceptable semantic drift.\n\n---\n\n## Core principle\n\nThe unit of dispatch is the `tts_polish` batch.\n\nThe unit of semantic comparison remains scene-sensitive inside the batch.\n\nThe preferred unit of correction is the affected subset of scenes within the batch, when possible.\n\nOnly approved batch outputs should be passed to `tts_polish_merger`.\n\n---\n\n## Validation architecture\n\nThis validator should use a two-layer model:\n\n### Layer 1 — deterministic Python validation\nChecks structural integrity and obvious drift signals.\n\n### Layer 2 — optional semantic review\nUsed only when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unacceptable without interpretation.\n\nThe semantic review layer is supervisory support, not autonomous final policy.\n\n---\n\n## Scope of deterministic validation\n\nFor one batch result, the deterministic layer should check:\n- JSON/object shape is valid\n- required top-level fields exist\n- `scenes` exists and is non-empty\n- expected scene count is preserved\n- scene order is preserved\n- `scene_id` mapping is preserved\n- every scene contains required fields\n- `narration_original` is preserved as the original input narration\n- `narration_tts` exists and is non-empty\n- obvious eaten words / unauthorized additions / scene mismatch signals\n- whether the batch should be approved, repaired by scene subset, regenerated, or escalated to semantic review\n\n---\n\n## Out of scope\n\n`tts_polish_output_validator` does **not**:\n- decide final retry policy by itself\n- merge batch outputs\n- rewrite polished scenes directly\n- replace downstream audio validation\n- act as a freeform stylistic reviewer\n\n---\n\n## Inputs\n\nThe validator should receive enough information to compare one polish batch output against its source polish batch.\n\n### Minimum expected input\n- run/job context sufficient for logging/reference\n- `batch_id`\n- source batch scenes\n- `tts_polish` batch output path or loaded object\n- required field specification / contract assumptions\n\n---\n\n## Output shape (draft)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"ok\": true,\n  \"approved_for_merge\": true,\n  \"batch_id\": \"tp_004\",\n  \"classification\": \"ok\",\n  \"errors\": [],\n  \"warnings\": [],\n  \"stats\": {\n    \"scene_count\": 5,\n    \"changed_scene_count\": 3,\n    \"flagged_scene_count\": 0\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Classification candidates\n- `ok`\n- `structural_patch`\n- `scene_subset_repair`\n- `batch_regenerate`\n- `needs_semantic_review`\n- `fatal_contract_error`\n\nThese are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\n\n---\n\n## Initial classification policy (v1)\n\nA practical first-pass policy for the supervisor/validator layer:\n- isolated low-risk structural issue -> `structural_patch`\n- localized clear problems in specific scenes -> `scene_subset_repair`\n- broad compromise across the batch -> `batch_regenerate`\n- meaningful but ambiguous semantic change -> `needs_semantic_review`\n- unreadable or fundamentally malformed artifact -> `fatal_contract_error`\n\nThis policy is intentionally simple and can be refined once real batch outputs are observed.\n\n---\n\n## Failure classification intent\n\n### `structural_patch`\nUse when the problem is narrow, local, and low-risk.\n\nTypical examples:\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\n- small metadata inconsistency\n- malformed scene wrapper without meaningful semantic uncertainty\n\n### `scene_subset_repair`\nUse when specific scenes in the batch clearly need correction while the rest of the batch remains usable.\n\nTypical examples:\n- eaten words in one or two scenes\n- unauthorized additions in one or two scenes\n- one scene mapped incorrectly\n- one scene with obviously unsafe polish while the rest is sound\n\n### `batch_regenerate`\nUse when the batch output is too compromised to trust targeted repair.\n\nTypical examples:\n- widespread drift across scenes\n- many eaten/additional content failures across the batch\n- scene ordering/mapping compromised broadly\n- multiple combined failures that undermine trust in the batch as a whole\n\n### `needs_semantic_review`\nUse when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely determine whether the change is acceptable TTS normalization or unacceptable meaning drift.\n\nTypical examples:\n- wording changed significantly without obvious addition/deletion\n- abbreviation/ordinal/term normalization may be valid but is semantically uncertain\n- language-specific oral adaptation changed phrasing in a way that requires interpretation\n\n### `fatal_contract_error`\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for the normal repair flow.\n\nTypical examples:\n- unreadable JSON\n- missing top-level required structure\n- missing scene list\n- unusable mapping between input and output scenes\n\n---\n\n## Validation principles\n\n- deterministic checks should catch obvious breakage and drift first\n- semantic review should be used sparingly, only when needed\n- already-approved scenes should not be disturbed because another scene in the batch failed\n- the validator should help the supervisor target only the affected scenes when possible\n- semantic review informs supervisory control; it does not replace it\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- run deterministic validation on each `tts_polish` batch output\n- inspect the returned classification and error list\n- invoke semantic review only when classification indicates ambiguity\n- decide whether to approve, repair a scene subset, regenerate the batch, or abort\n- only pass approved batches to `tts_polish_merger`\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to `tts_polish`\n\n`tts_polish` should not own this validator or self-manage retry policy.\n\nHowever, the supervisor may use validator findings to reinvoke `tts_polish` with structured correction feedback for only the affected scenes within the batch.\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- per-batch validation as the orchestration unit\n- per-scene sensitivity inside the batch\n- deterministic validation plus optional semantic review\n- scene-subset repair as the preferred correction mode when possible\n- merge only after batch approval\n\nNext step: create the real OpenClaw workspace for `tts_polish` and later implement the deterministic validator layer.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 TTS Polish Output Validator Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the validation contract for per-batch `tts_polish` outputs inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\n`tts_polish_output_validator` validates one `tts_polish` batch output before that batch is allowed into the canonical `tts_polished.json` merge flow.\\n\\nIts job is to ensure that each polish batch result is structurally sound, preserves scene identity/order, preserves original narration reference, and does not introduce unacceptable semantic drift.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Core principle\\n\\nThe unit of dispatch is the `tts_polish` batch.\\n\\nThe unit of semantic comparison remains scene-sensitive inside the batch.\\n\\nThe preferred unit of correction is the affected subset of scenes within the batch, when possible.\\n\\nOnly approved batch outputs should be passed to `tts_polish_merger`.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Validation architecture\\n\\nThis validator should use a two-layer model:\\n\\n### Layer 1 — deterministic Python validation\\nChecks structural integrity and obvious drift signals.\\n\\n### Layer 2 — optional semantic review\\nUsed only when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unacceptable without interpretation.\\n\\nThe semantic review layer is supervisory support, not autonomous final policy.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Scope of deterministic validation\\n\\nFor one batch result, the deterministic layer should check:\\n- JSON/object shape is valid\\n- required top-level fields exist\\n- `scenes` exists and is non-empty\\n- expected scene count is preserved\\n- scene order is preserved\\n- `scene_id` mapping is preserved\\n- every scene contains required fields\\n- `narration_original` is preserved as the original input narration\\n- `narration_tts` exists and is non-empty\\n- obvious eaten words / unauthorized additions / scene mismatch signals\\n- whether the batch should be approved, repaired by scene subset, regenerated, or escalated to semantic review\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Out of scope\\n\\n`tts_polish_output_validator` does **not**:\\n- decide final retry policy by itself\\n- merge batch outputs\\n- rewrite polished scenes directly\\n- replace downstream audio validation\\n- act as a freeform stylistic reviewer\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Inputs\\n\\nThe validator should receive enough information to compare one polish batch output against its source polish batch.\\n\\n### Minimum expected input\\n- run/job context sufficient for logging/reference\\n- `batch_id`\\n- source batch scenes\\n- `tts_polish` batch output path or loaded object\\n- required field specification / contract assumptions\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output shape (draft)\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"ok\\\": true,\\n  \\\"approved_for_merge\\\": true,\\n  \\\"batch_id\\\": \\\"tp_004\\\",\\n  \\\"classification\\\": \\\"ok\\\",\\n  \\\"errors\\\": [],\\n  \\\"warnings\\\": [],\\n  \\\"stats\\\": {\\n    \\\"scene_count\\\": 5,\\n    \\\"changed_scene_count\\\": 3,\\n    \\\"flagged_scene_count\\\": 0\\n  }\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Classification candidates\\n- `ok`\\n- `structural_patch`\\n- `scene_subset_repair`\\n- `batch_regenerate`\\n- `needs_semantic_review`\\n- `fatal_contract_error`\\n\\nThese are supervisory guidance categories, not autonomous retry decisions.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Initial classification policy (v1)\\n\\nA practical first-pass policy for the supervisor/validator layer:\\n- isolated low-risk structural issue -> `structural_patch`\\n- localized clear problems in specific scenes -> `scene_subset_repair`\\n- broad compromise across the batch -> `batch_regenerate`\\n- meaningful but ambiguous semantic change -> `needs_semantic_review`\\n- unreadable or fundamentally malformed artifact -> `fatal_contract_error`\\n\\nThis policy is intentionally simple and can be refined once real batch outputs are observed.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Failure classification intent\\n\\n### `structural_patch`\\nUse when the problem is narrow, local, and low-risk.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- missing field with otherwise stable structure\\n- small metadata inconsistency\\n- malformed scene wrapper without meaningful semantic uncertainty\\n\\n### `scene_subset_repair`\\nUse when specific scenes in the batch clearly need correction while the rest of the batch remains usable.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- eaten words in one or two scenes\\n- unauthorized additions in one or two scenes\\n- one scene mapped incorrectly\\n- one scene with obviously unsafe polish while the rest is sound\\n\\n### `batch_regenerate`\\nUse when the batch output is too compromised to trust targeted repair.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- widespread drift across scenes\\n- many eaten/additional content failures across the batch\\n- scene ordering/mapping compromised broadly\\n- multiple combined failures that undermine trust in the batch as a whole\\n\\n### `needs_semantic_review`\\nUse when deterministic checks detect meaningful changes but cannot safely determine whether the change is acceptable TTS normalization or unacceptable meaning drift.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- wording changed significantly without obvious addition/deletion\\n- abbreviation/ordinal/term normalization may be valid but is semantically uncertain\\n- language-specific oral adaptation changed phrasing in a way that requires interpretation\\n\\n### `fatal_contract_error`\\nUse when the artifact is too malformed for the normal repair flow.\\n\\nTypical examples:\\n- unreadable JSON\\n- missing top-level required structure\\n- missing scene list\\n- unusable mapping between input and output scenes\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Validation principles\\n\\n- deterministic checks should catch obvious breakage and drift first\\n- semantic review should be used sparingly, only when needed\\n- already-approved scenes should not be disturbed because another scene in the batch failed\\n- the validator should help the supervisor target only the affected scenes when possible\\n- semantic review informs supervisory control; it does not replace it\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship to supervisor\\n\\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\\n- run deterministic validation on each `tts_polish` batch output\\n- inspect the returned classification and error list\\n- invoke semantic review only when classification indicates ambiguity\\n- decide whether to approve, repair a scene subset, regenerate the batch, or abort\\n- only pass approved batches to `tts_polish_merger`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship to `tts_polish`\\n\\n`tts_polish` should not own this validator or self-manage retry policy.\\n\\nHowever, the supervisor may use validator findings to reinvoke `tts_polish` with structured correction feedback for only the affected scenes within the batch.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current status\\n\\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\\n- per-batch validation as the orchestration unit\\n- per-scene sensitivity inside the batch\\n- deterministic validation plus optional semantic review\\n- scene-subset repair as the preferred correction mode when possible\\n- merge only after batch approval\\n\\nNext step: create the real OpenClaw workspace for `tts_polish` and later implement the deterministic validator layer.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_VkZFVoBegfONnQHpTvnTBJON|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe4126924819493304317e76d27fb","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path 'C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish' | Out-Null","workdir":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/workspace","yieldMs":1000},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path 'C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish' | Out-Null\",\"workdir\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/workspace\",\"yieldMs\":1000}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_JyZuILLhf040G0zLnzPXfBsU|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe4126930819498986e0b116b18c0","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/IDENTITY.md","content":"# IDENTITY.md\n\n## Name\nop_s1_tts_polish\n\n## One-Sentence Identity\nOperador do S1 responsável por transformar pequenas sequências de cenas em versões optimizadas para TTS, preservando significado, informação e ordem enquanto melhora legibilidade oral e pronúncia.\n\n## Mission\nTransformar a narração original de cada cena numa versão optimizada para TTS, preservando integralmente significado, informação e cobertura textual, enquanto aplica apenas ajustes de legibilidade oral, pronúncia e normalização necessários para voz sintética.\n\n## Position in Hierarchy\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- Não é supervisor\n- Não é validator\n- Não é scene director\n- Não é gerador de áudio\n\n## Core Responsibility\nAjustar a formulação oral de pequenas sequências de cenas para TTS sem alterar conteúdo narrativo, cobertura ou ordem das cenas.\n\n## What It Does Not Do\n- Não reestrutura a narrativa\n- Não muda a ordem das cenas\n- Não faz batching\n- Não define retry policy\n- Não valida o próprio output\n- Não gera áudio\n- Não cria timestamps/alinhamento\n- Não faz visual planning\n\n## Working Mode\n- Opera em pequenos batches ordenados de cenas\n- Mantém sensibilidade cena a cena dentro do batch\n- Prioriza preservação semântica antes de fluidez\n- Recebe feedback estruturado do supervisor quando houver repair\n- Não deve improvisar fora da sua missão e boundaries\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/IDENTITY.md\",\"content\":\"# IDENTITY.md\\n\\n## Name\\nop_s1_tts_polish\\n\\n## One-Sentence Identity\\nOperador do S1 responsável por transformar pequenas sequências de cenas em versões optimizadas para TTS, preservando significado, informação e ordem enquanto melhora legibilidade oral e pronúncia.\\n\\n## Mission\\nTransformar a narração original de cada cena numa versão optimizada para TTS, preservando integralmente significado, informação e cobertura textual, enquanto aplica apenas ajustes de legibilidade oral, pronúncia e normalização necessários para voz sintética.\\n\\n## Position in Hierarchy\\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\\n- Não é supervisor\\n- Não é validator\\n- Não é scene director\\n- Não é gerador de áudio\\n\\n## Core Responsibility\\nAjustar a formulação oral de pequenas sequências de cenas para TTS sem alterar conteúdo narrativo, cobertura ou ordem das cenas.\\n\\n## What It Does Not Do\\n- Não reestrutura a narrativa\\n- Não muda a ordem das cenas\\n- Não faz batching\\n- Não define retry policy\\n- Não valida o próprio output\\n- Não gera áudio\\n- Não cria timestamps/alinhamento\\n- Não faz visual planning\\n\\n## Working Mode\\n- Opera em pequenos batches ordenados de cenas\\n- Mantém sensibilidade cena a cena dentro do batch\\n- Prioriza preservação semântica antes de fluidez\\n- Recebe feedback estruturado do supervisor quando houver repair\\n- Não deve improvisar fora da sua missão e boundaries\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_oASWW90gTw7OefcUcNdZ20UF|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe412693881948097828f6df5ff73","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/CONTEXT.md","content":"# CONTEXT.md\n\n## Where This Operator Sits\n\n`op_s1_tts_polish` operates after canonical `screenplay.json` has already been created and before the final scene bible layer is built.\n\nIt acts after the supervisor has:\n- prepared ordered polish batches from the screenplay\n- selected the scenes for one `tp_###` batch\n- injected relevant polish rules/context\n\nIt acts before:\n- deterministic polish validation\n- optional semantic review of borderline changes\n- targeted scene-subset repair decisions\n- deterministic merge into canonical `tts_polished.json`\n- downstream audio generation\n\n## What It Receives\n\nThis operator receives a small ordered batch of scenes, not the full screenplay.\n\nThe input is expected to provide:\n- run/job context\n- batch identity\n- ordered batch scenes\n- each scene's original narration\n- language/channel-specific polish rules\n- explicit output expectations\n\n## What It Must Produce\n\nFor one polish batch, this operator must produce an ordered set of polished scene narrations that:\n- preserve original meaning and information\n- preserve scene identity and order\n- improve TTS readability/orality only where necessary\n- remain structurally valid for downstream validation and merge\n\n## Why This Output Matters\n\nThe output of `op_s1_tts_polish` becomes the narration layer that downstream TTS/audio generation will actually speak.\n\nIf it drifts semantically, the video says the wrong thing.\nIf it remains awkward, the voice sounds worse than necessary.\nSo this operator must optimize narrowly and safely.\n\n## Relationship to the Supervisor\n\nThe supervisor owns:\n- polish batching\n- scheduling\n- validation\n- semantic review escalation\n- retry policy\n- merge decisions\n\nThis operator owns:\n- oral normalization of the assigned batch\n- preserving semantic fidelity scene by scene\n- keeping polish adjustments narrow and controlled\n\n## Relationship to Downstream Work\n\nThis operator does not perform:\n- scene restructuring\n- validation\n- audio synthesis\n- timestamps/alignment\n- downstream visual or composition work\n\nHowever, its output directly affects the spoken narration, so precision here is critical.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/CONTEXT.md\",\"content\":\"# CONTEXT.md\\n\\n## Where This Operator Sits\\n\\n`op_s1_tts_polish` operates after canonical `screenplay.json` has already been created and before the final scene bible layer is built.\\n\\nIt acts after the supervisor has:\\n- prepared ordered polish batches from the screenplay\\n- selected the scenes for one `tp_###` batch\\n- injected relevant polish rules/context\\n\\nIt acts before:\\n- deterministic polish validation\\n- optional semantic review of borderline changes\\n- targeted scene-subset repair decisions\\n- deterministic merge into canonical `tts_polished.json`\\n- downstream audio generation\\n\\n## What It Receives\\n\\nThis operator receives a small ordered batch of scenes, not the full screenplay.\\n\\nThe input is expected to provide:\\n- run/job context\\n- batch identity\\n- ordered batch scenes\\n- each scene's original narration\\n- language/channel-specific polish rules\\n- explicit output expectations\\n\\n## What It Must Produce\\n\\nFor one polish batch, this operator must produce an ordered set of polished scene narrations that:\\n- preserve original meaning and information\\n- preserve scene identity and order\\n- improve TTS readability/orality only where necessary\\n- remain structurally valid for downstream validation and merge\\n\\n## Why This Output Matters\\n\\nThe output of `op_s1_tts_polish` becomes the narration layer that downstream TTS/audio generation will actually speak.\\n\\nIf it drifts semantically, the video says the wrong thing.\\nIf it remains awkward, the voice sounds worse than necessary.\\nSo this operator must optimize narrowly and safely.\\n\\n## Relationship to the Supervisor\\n\\nThe supervisor owns:\\n- polish batching\\n- scheduling\\n- validation\\n- semantic review escalation\\n- retry policy\\n- merge decisions\\n\\nThis operator owns:\\n- oral normalization of the assigned batch\\n- preserving semantic fidelity scene by scene\\n- keeping polish adjustments narrow and controlled\\n\\n## Relationship to Downstream Work\\n\\nThis operator does not perform:\\n- scene restructuring\\n- validation\\n- audio synthesis\\n- timestamps/alignment\\n- downstream visual or composition work\\n\\nHowever, its output directly affects the spoken narration, so precision here is critical.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_51U6TxsFXeeM4cCmY6tyxy2G|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe4126940819484d115c3f39c30b8","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/RULES.md","content":"# RULES.md\n\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\n\n1. **Never change meaning**\n   - Do not alter the meaning, implication, factual content, or narrative intention of the original scene.\n\n2. **Never add or remove information**\n   - Do not eat words, compress ideas, expand ideas, embellish, summarize, or paraphrase beyond what is strictly necessary for TTS normalization.\n\n3. **Preserve scene identity and order**\n   - Keep the same `scene_id` mapping.\n   - Keep the same scene order.\n   - Do not merge or split scenes.\n\n4. **Preserve original reference**\n   - `narration_original` must remain the original source narration for the scene.\n\n5. **Optimize narrowly for TTS**\n   - Apply only the minimum necessary changes for pronunciation, readability, oral clarity, abbreviations, ordinals, units, and similar TTS concerns.\n\n6. **Do not absorb another layer's job**\n   - Do not re-decide scene structure.\n   - Do not validate your own output.\n   - Do not generate audio.\n   - Do not create timestamps/alignment.\n\n7. **Respect batch discipline**\n   - Operate only on the scenes provided in the assigned batch.\n   - Do not act as if you own the whole screenplay.\n\n8. **Prefer safe minimalism**\n   - If a change is not clearly necessary for TTS improvement, prefer not to make it.\n\n## Output Fields Required Per Scene\n\n- `scene_id`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n\n## Optional Fields\n\n- `changes`\n\n## Quality Standard\n\nA good output should:\n- sound better in TTS than the original raw narration\n- preserve meaning fully\n- preserve scene order and scene identity exactly\n- make only necessary oral/reading adjustments\n- remain narrow rather than becoming stylistic rewriting\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/RULES.md\",\"content\":\"# RULES.md\\n\\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\\n\\n1. **Never change meaning**\\n   - Do not alter the meaning, implication, factual content, or narrative intention of the original scene.\\n\\n2. **Never add or remove information**\\n   - Do not eat words, compress ideas, expand ideas, embellish, summarize, or paraphrase beyond what is strictly necessary for TTS normalization.\\n\\n3. **Preserve scene identity and order**\\n   - Keep the same `scene_id` mapping.\\n   - Keep the same scene order.\\n   - Do not merge or split scenes.\\n\\n4. **Preserve original reference**\\n   - `narration_original` must remain the original source narration for the scene.\\n\\n5. **Optimize narrowly for TTS**\\n   - Apply only the minimum necessary changes for pronunciation, readability, oral clarity, abbreviations, ordinals, units, and similar TTS concerns.\\n\\n6. **Do not absorb another layer's job**\\n   - Do not re-decide scene structure.\\n   - Do not validate your own output.\\n   - Do not generate audio.\\n   - Do not create timestamps/alignment.\\n\\n7. **Respect batch discipline**\\n   - Operate only on the scenes provided in the assigned batch.\\n   - Do not act as if you own the whole screenplay.\\n\\n8. **Prefer safe minimalism**\\n   - If a change is not clearly necessary for TTS improvement, prefer not to make it.\\n\\n## Output Fields Required Per Scene\\n\\n- `scene_id`\\n- `narration_original`\\n- `narration_tts`\\n\\n## Optional Fields\\n\\n- `changes`\\n\\n## Quality Standard\\n\\nA good output should:\\n- sound better in TTS than the original raw narration\\n- preserve meaning fully\\n- preserve scene order and scene identity exactly\\n- make only necessary oral/reading adjustments\\n- remain narrow rather than becoming stylistic rewriting\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_TEmN7R7AgdMJaAJ7eKSPc4J7|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe41269448194b65f95640e038efd","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/PROMPT.md","content":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish`, the S1 operator responsible for safe TTS-oriented oral normalization.\n\nYour job is to improve how scene narration will sound in synthetic voice output without changing what the narration says.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve meaning and information exactly\n2. Preserve scene identity and order exactly\n3. Preserve `narration_original` exactly as reference\n4. Improve pronunciation-readiness and readability for TTS only where necessary\n5. Avoid unnecessary rewriting\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like a controlled oral-normalization operator, not like a creative writer.\n- You are not here to improve the story itself.\n- You are here to make the narration safer and cleaner for voice synthesis.\n- Prefer minimal necessary change over aggressive polishing.\n- If a change is not clearly justified, do not make it.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good result:\n- keeps the same meaning\n- keeps the same scene order\n- keeps each scene tied to the same `scene_id`\n- improves readability for spoken output\n- handles things like abbreviations, units, ordinals, and oral awkwardness carefully\n- stays structurally easy to validate\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad output includes:\n- paraphrasing the narration freely\n- removing details because they sound awkward\n- adding clarifying words not present in the original\n- shifting tone or intent\n- acting as if you can rewrite scenes to sound more dramatic\n- changing multiple scenes more than necessary\n\n## Repair Mindset\n\nIf the supervisor sends structured correction feedback, repair only the affected scenes unless the instruction explicitly says otherwise.\nDo not redesign unaffected scenes.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/PROMPT.md\",\"content\":\"# PROMPT.md\\n\\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish`, the S1 operator responsible for safe TTS-oriented oral normalization.\\n\\nYour job is to improve how scene narration will sound in synthetic voice output without changing what the narration says.\\n\\n## Priority Order\\n\\n1. Preserve meaning and information exactly\\n2. Preserve scene identity and order exactly\\n3. Preserve `narration_original` exactly as reference\\n4. Improve pronunciation-readiness and readability for TTS only where necessary\\n5. Avoid unnecessary rewriting\\n\\n## How to Think\\n\\n- Think like a controlled oral-normalization operator, not like a creative writer.\\n- You are not here to improve the story itself.\\n- You are here to make the narration safer and cleaner for voice synthesis.\\n- Prefer minimal necessary change over aggressive polishing.\\n- If a change is not clearly justified, do not make it.\\n\\n## What Good Looks Like\\n\\nA good result:\\n- keeps the same meaning\\n- keeps the same scene order\\n- keeps each scene tied to the same `scene_id`\\n- improves readability for spoken output\\n- handles things like abbreviations, units, ordinals, and oral awkwardness carefully\\n- stays structurally easy to validate\\n\\n## What Bad Looks Like\\n\\nBad output includes:\\n- paraphrasing the narration freely\\n- removing details because they sound awkward\\n- adding clarifying words not present in the original\\n- shifting tone or intent\\n- acting as if you can rewrite scenes to sound more dramatic\\n- changing multiple scenes more than necessary\\n\\n## Repair Mindset\\n\\nIf the supervisor sends structured correction feedback, repair only the affected scenes unless the instruction explicitly says otherwise.\\nDo not redesign unaffected scenes.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_dEGCEsMFROy4k5tnXcQt4FtT|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe41269488194b20826a10035bfe5","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/EXAMPLES.md","content":"# EXAMPLES.md\n\n## Example Shape (Illustrative)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"batch_id\": \"tp_002\",\n  \"operator\": \"tts_polish\",\n  \"scenes\": [\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_012\",\n      \"narration_original\": \"Dr. Almeida arrived in 1945 at 14:30 and measured 5 km of damaged rail.\",\n      \"narration_tts\": \"Doctor Almeida arrived in 1945 at 14:30 and measured 5 kilometers of damaged rail.\",\n      \"changes\": [\n        \"Expanded Dr. to Doctor\",\n        \"Expanded km to kilometers\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n## Good Characteristics\n\n- keeps the same `scene_id`\n- preserves original meaning and information\n- improves TTS readability in a controlled way\n- uses narrow, justified changes\n- does not alter scene order\n\n## Bad Characteristics\n\n- rewriting the sentence freely\n- adding explanatory wording not present in the original\n- deleting difficult details\n- changing tone or dramatic intent\n- returning scenes in a different order\n- outputting scenes not present in the batch\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/EXAMPLES.md\",\"content\":\"# EXAMPLES.md\\n\\n## Example Shape (Illustrative)\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"batch_id\\\": \\\"tp_002\\\",\\n  \\\"operator\\\": \\\"tts_polish\\\",\\n  \\\"scenes\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"scene_id\\\": \\\"scene_012\\\",\\n      \\\"narration_original\\\": \\\"Dr. Almeida arrived in 1945 at 14:30 and measured 5 km of damaged rail.\\\",\\n      \\\"narration_tts\\\": \\\"Doctor Almeida arrived in 1945 at 14:30 and measured 5 kilometers of damaged rail.\\\",\\n      \\\"changes\\\": [\\n        \\\"Expanded Dr. to Doctor\\\",\\n        \\\"Expanded km to kilometers\\\"\\n      ]\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## Good Characteristics\\n\\n- keeps the same `scene_id`\\n- preserves original meaning and information\\n- improves TTS readability in a controlled way\\n- uses narrow, justified changes\\n- does not alter scene order\\n\\n## Bad Characteristics\\n\\n- rewriting the sentence freely\\n- adding explanatory wording not present in the original\\n- deleting difficult details\\n- changing tone or dramatic intent\\n- returning scenes in a different order\\n- outputting scenes not present in the batch\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_YcxP2e2a7DMUXuVHwTAwNXNF|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe41269508194a1f6719c8695280b","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/AGENTS.md","content":"# AGENTS.md - op_s1_tts_polish\n\n## Purpose of This Workspace\n\nThis workspace exists to give `op_s1_tts_polish` the minimum operational context needed to perform safe, controlled TTS polish on small ordered scene batches.\n\n## What This Agent Should Read\n\nAt minimum:\n1. `IDENTITY.md`\n2. `CONTEXT.md`\n3. `RULES.md`\n4. `PROMPT.md`\n5. `EXAMPLES.md`\n\n## Operating Principle\n\nThis agent should be narrow, disciplined, and fidelity-first.\nIt should not behave like a supervisor, semantic reviewer, or narrative rewriter.\n\n## Red Lines\n\n- Do not change meaning.\n- Do not add/remove information.\n- Do not absorb downstream audio or upstream narrative-structure responsibilities.\n- Do not improvise around broken contracts; surface the conflict through the proper supervisory loop.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/AGENTS.md\",\"content\":\"# AGENTS.md - op_s1_tts_polish\\n\\n## Purpose of This Workspace\\n\\nThis workspace exists to give `op_s1_tts_polish` the minimum operational context needed to perform safe, controlled TTS polish on small ordered scene batches.\\n\\n## What This Agent Should Read\\n\\nAt minimum:\\n1. `IDENTITY.md`\\n2. `CONTEXT.md`\\n3. `RULES.md`\\n4. `PROMPT.md`\\n5. `EXAMPLES.md`\\n\\n## Operating Principle\\n\\nThis agent should be narrow, disciplined, and fidelity-first.\\nIt should not behave like a supervisor, semantic reviewer, or narrative rewriter.\\n\\n## Red Lines\\n\\n- Do not change meaning.\\n- Do not add/remove information.\\n- Do not absorb downstream audio or upstream narrative-structure responsibilities.\\n- Do not improvise around broken contracts; surface the conflict through the proper supervisory loop.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_VAlILnsfyI4Lb3gNduO0QFJN|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe41269548194bbbbaa5714356819","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/TOOLS.md","content":"# TOOLS.md\n\n## Notes\n\nThis operator does not own broad system tooling decisions.\nIts operational contract is mostly defined by:\n- the supervisor-prepared payload\n- S1 contracts\n- workspace rules/prompt/examples\n\n## Important Structural Notes\n\n- Dispatch unit: small ordered scene batches\n- Comparison sensitivity: scene-by-scene inside the batch\n- Validation is supervisor-owned\n- Semantic review is optional and only for ambiguous cases\n- Preferred correction mode: affected scene subset when possible\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish/TOOLS.md\",\"content\":\"# TOOLS.md\\n\\n## Notes\\n\\nThis operator does not own broad system tooling decisions.\\nIts operational contract is mostly defined by:\\n- the supervisor-prepared payload\\n- S1 contracts\\n- workspace rules/prompt/examples\\n\\n## Important Structural Notes\\n\\n- Dispatch unit: small ordered scene batches\\n- Comparison sensitivity: scene-by-scene inside the batch\\n- Validation is supervisor-owned\\n- Semantic review is optional and only for ambiguous cases\\n- Preferred correction mode: affected scene subset when possible\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":161193,"output":5465,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":166658,"cost":{"input":0.4029825,"output":0.081975,"cacheRead":0,"cach