{"type":"message","id":"581ddc65","parentId":"9fca1065","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:11:31.022Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Feito. Avancei em tudo isso de uma vez.\n\n# O que foi criado\n\n## Contracts no repo\nEm:\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\Desktop\\content-factory\\auto_content_factory\\docs\\contracts\\s1\\`\n\ncriei:\n\n- `s1_tts_polish_contract.md`\n- `s1_tts_polish_output_validator_contract.md`\n\n---\n\n## Workspace real do OpenClaw\nEm:\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish\\`\n\ncriei:\n\n- `AGENTS.md`\n- `IDENTITY.md`\n- `CONTEXT.md`\n- `RULES.md`\n- `PROMPT.md`\n- `EXAMPLES.md`\n- `TOOLS.md`\n\n---\n\n# O que ficou definido no `tts_polish`\n\n## Contract do operator\nFicou estabelecido:\n- missão\n- responsabilidade central\n- posição no S1\n- small-batch execution model\n- input contract\n- output contract\n- boundaries\n- validation/correction loop\n\n## Pontos-chave\n- dispatch por **pequenos batches de cenas**\n- sensibilidade semântica **cena a cena dentro do batch**\n- `tts_polish` não é rewriter livre\n- preferred correction mode = **subset de cenas afectadas quando possível**\n\n---\n\n## Contract do validator\nFicou estabelecido:\n- duas camadas:\n  - **deterministic Python validation**\n  - **optional semantic review**\n- classificações:\n  - `ok`\n  - `structural_patch`\n  - `scene_subset_repair`\n  - `batch_regenerate`\n  - `needs_semantic_review`\n  - `fatal_contract_error`\n\n### e também:\n- o supervisor é quem usa isso\n- semantic review é suporte, não política final\n- merge só depois de batch aprovado\n\n---\n\n## Workspace real do `op_s1_tts_polish`\nFicou com:\n- identidade clara\n- contexto operacional\n- regras fortes\n- prompt disciplinado\n- exemplos\n- notas estruturais\n\n---\n\n# Onde estamos agora\nNeste momento já temos, de forma relativamente madura:\n\n## S1 Supervisor\n- contract consolidado\n\n## `scene_director`\n- contract\n- validator contract\n- workspace real\n- skill Python criada\n- runtime razoavelmente alinhado\n\n## `tts_polish`\n- contract\n- validator contract\n- workspace real\n\n---\n\n# Próximo passo lógico\nAgora eu vejo dois caminhos possíveis:\n\n## opção A\nfazer uma recapitulação curta do estado actual de S1 depois dessas criações, para não voltarmos a perder o fio\n\n## opção B\ncomeçar a decidir:\n**qual é a próxima skill/peça do supervisor que realmente merece contract próprio separado**\n\n### Minha recomendação\n**Opção A primeiro**, bem curta.  \nPorque acabámos de abrir mais duas frentes de ficheiro, e vale consolidar antes de seguir.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe41b6e808194bbefbd2bca9185c6\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":147412,"output":615,"cacheRead":16896,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":164923,"cost":{"input":0.36853,"output":0.009225,"cacheRead":0.0042239999999999995,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.381979}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774969876308,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe417573c8194964a693462f32bb5"}}
{"type":"message","id":"935c1c71","parentId":"581ddc65","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:17:05.618Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 12:17 GMT-3] Bora ja definir este reviwer ai como vamos estruturar Tobias pra ficar 100% e ai só revisarmos o workflow do S1 completo ver as outras skills ver os contratosd ver os docs no workspace dos agentes para entender se tudo fecha se ta tudo atualizado tudo mais? Temo scnebible tbm que quero lembrar como que ele vai ser criado agora com essas diferenças e tal"}],"timestamp":1774970225537}}
{"type":"message","id":"5bcae16f","parentId":"935c1c71","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:17:38.244Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Perfeito. E sim — essa é a sequência certa.\n\nAntes de “revisar tudo e ver se fecha”, faz sentido **fechar a peça do semantic reviewer do `tts_polish`**, porque ela ainda está só como conceito dentro do loop.\n\nE depois disso fazemos uma revisão sistémica do S1:\n- workflow\n- skills\n- contracts\n- workspaces\n- scene_bible com o shape novo\n\nIsso é exactamente o tipo de consolidação que evita drift.\n\n---\n\n# Próximo foco: semantic reviewer do `tts_polish`\n\n## O que precisamos decidir\nA pergunta principal é:\n\n> essa peça é uma **skill**, um **operator**, ou um **submodo do supervisor**?\n\nMinha leitura: **não deve ser skill Python**.\n\nPorque a função dela é:\n- julgar borderline semanticamente\n- interpretar se uma mudança é aceitável ou drift\n- decidir se uma adaptação de TTS faz sentido linguístico\n\nIsso pede **julgamento semântico**, não só regra dura.\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação\n## Tratar como um reviewer semântico leve, sob o supervisor\nEu vejo duas opções boas:\n\n### opção A — operator dedicado\nAlgo tipo:\n- `op_s1_tts_polish_reviewer`\n\n### opção B — reviewer auxiliar sem workspace próprio robusto, quase como subagente de revisão\nMais leve, menos “agente identitário”\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação real\n## Começar tratando como peça lógica dedicada, mas **sem inflar cedo demais**\nOu seja:\n- dar contract próprio\n- definir o papel claramente\n- mas ainda não assumir que precisa de um workspace tão pesado quanto `scene_director` e `tts_polish`\n\nPorque ele não é operador principal do pipeline.\nEle é:\n> **camada de arbitragem semântica para casos ambíguos**\n\n---\n\n# Papel exacto do reviewer\nMinha proposta:\n\n## Missão\n**Julgar se alterações borderline feitas pelo `tts_polish` são aceitáveis como normalização para TTS ou se constituem drift semântico indevido, devolvendo um parecer accionável para o supervisor.**\n\n---\n\n# O que ele **não** faz\n- não faz polish\n- não faz validação estrutural\n- não define batching\n- não decide retry policy sozinho\n- não substitui o supervisor\n- não revê tudo sempre\n- não é chamado em casos óbvios\n\nOu seja:\n- só entra quando a camada Python diz:\n  - `needs_semantic_review`\n\n---\n\n# Input dele\nMinha proposta:\n\nele recebe **só o material necessário para arbitrar o caso**:\n\n- `batch_id`\n- subset de cenas afectadas\n- para cada cena afectada:\n  - `scene_id`\n  - `narration_original`\n  - `narration_tts`\n- talvez `changes`, se existir\n- lista de flags/razões vindas do validator Python\n- contexto de idioma/regras aplicáveis\n\n### ponto importante\nEle não precisa receber o batch inteiro sempre.\nEu tenderia a dizer:\n> **recebe só as cenas problemáticas**, salvo se houver razão forte para mandar o batch todo.\n\n---\n\n# Output dele\nAqui acho importante ser muito accionável para o supervisor.\n\n## Proposta\nPara cada cena revista, ele devolve algo como:\n\n- `scene_id`\n- `judgment`\n- `reason`\n- `recommended_action`\n\n### `judgment`\n- `acceptable_tts_normalization`\n- `unsafe_meaning_drift`\n- `unclear_but_repair_preferred`\n\n### `recommended_action`\n- `approve_scene`\n- `repair_scene`\n- `regenerate_batch_if_needed`\n\n---\n\n# Classificação mais simples possível\nSe quisermos manter simples na v1, eu até reduziria para:\n\n## julgamento por cena\n- `approve`\n- `repair`\n- `escalate`\n\nMas eu pessoalmente gosto mais da versão um pouco mais explícita:\n- porque ajuda a documentar o rational\n\n---\n\n# Como isso entra no loop\n## Fluxo completo do `tts_polish`\n1. supervisor envia batch ao `tts_polish`\n2. `tts_polish` devolve output\n3. validator Python roda\n4. se:\n   - `ok` → aprova\n   - `scene_subset_repair` → pede repair directo\n   - `batch_regenerate` → regenera batch\n   - `needs_semantic_review` → chama reviewer\n5. reviewer devolve parecer por cena\n6. supervisor decide:\n   - aprovar cena(s)\n   - pedir repair subset\n   - regenerar batch\n   - abortar / escalar\n\n---\n\n# Minha opinião sobre o nome\n## Contract\n`s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md`\n\n## Peça lógica\n`tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`\n\nSe mais tarde virar agent/workspace real:\n- `op_s1_tts_polish_reviewer`\nou\n- `rv_s1_tts_polish_semantic`\n\n### Minha preferência agora\nFicar só com o nome lógico:\n- **`tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`**\n\ne só depois decidir se merece workspace real próprio.\n\n---\n\n# Pergunta importante: isso deve ter workspace próprio agora?\n## Minha resposta:\n**eu ainda não criaria workspace próprio agora**\n\nPorque antes precisamos responder:\n- ele é frequente o suficiente?\n- ele vai operar como peça estável do sistema?\n- ou é só um reviewer auxiliar invocado raramente?\n\n### Minha recomendação\n1. criar **contract**\n2. definir loop\n3. depois revisar o workflow completo do S1\n4. só então decidir se ele merece workspace real próprio\n\n---\n\n# Sobre a tua segunda parte: “e depois revisar o workflow completo do S1”\nSim. E eu acho que isso é exactamente o movimento certo **depois** deste contract do reviewer.\n\nPorque nessa revisão vamos conseguir olhar:\n- supervisor\n- scene_director\n- scene_director validator\n- tts_polish\n- tts_polish validator\n- semantic reviewer\n- scene_bible\n- skills do supervisor\n- workspaces dos agents\n\nE perguntar:\n> fecha tudo? há drift? falta alguma peça? há naming torto? há docs velhas?\n\n---\n\n# Sobre o `scene_bible`\nTambém concordo 100%.\n\nDepois dessa revisão do reviewer, precisamos revisitar explicitamente:\n## como o `scene_bible` nasce agora\nporque ele mudou materialmente com:\n- `scene_title`\n- `scene_summary`\n- `narrative_function`\n- `narration_original`\n- `narration_tts`\n- campos que antes vinham cedo demais e agora não\n\nIsso merece uma revisão dedicada dentro do “workflow S1 completo”.\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação imediata\n## Ordem exacta\n1. fechar o **contract do `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`**\n2. depois fazer uma **revisão sistémica completa do S1**\n3. nessa revisão, parar explicitamente em:\n   - workflow\n   - skills\n   - contracts\n   - workspaces\n   - scene_bible\n\n---\n\nSe quiser, eu já avanço agora com uma proposta concreta do:\n\n## `s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md`\n\ncom:\n- missão\n- input\n- output\n- when invoked\n- out of scope\n- relationship with supervisor and validator\n\nE depois partimos para a revisão completa do S1.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe57873f481948853e79f7fc04ea6\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":322,"output":1543,"cacheRead":164736,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":166601,"cost":{"input":0.000805,"output":0.023145,"cacheRead":0.041184,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.065134}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774970227107,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe5769a0c8194be31e412c1af7b95"}}
{"type":"message","id":"e5cb1a91","parentId":"5bcae16f","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:18:42.214Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 12:18 GMT-3] navegando no direotiro do penclaw, eu vi que tem um direotiro chamado subagentes la dentro. Qual a diferença dos subagentes para agents?"}],"timestamp":1774970322133}}
{"type":"message","id":"839eff27","parentId":"e5cb1a91","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:18:58.310Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Boa pergunta. Aqui eu vou ser cuidadoso para não inventar além do que confirmei.\n\n## O que dá para afirmar com segurança\nDentro de `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\` nós vimos pelo menos estas pastas:\n- `agents`\n- `subagents`\n\n### `agents`\nPelo que já confirmámos na prática, `agents` é onde estão os **workspaces persistentes/definidos** dos agentes do teu sistema, por exemplo:\n- `main`\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- agora `op_s1_scene_director`\n- agora `op_s1_tts_polish`\n\nOu seja:\n> **`agents` = agentes nomeados, persistentes, com identidade/workspace próprio**\n\n---\n\n## Minha leitura sobre `subagents`\nPelo naming e pelo comportamento geral do OpenClaw, `subagents` tende a ser a área usada para:\n- execuções auxiliares\n- sessões subordinadas\n- runs/spawns derivados\n- coisas mais transitórias/operacionais do que agentes “canónicos” do sistema\n\nOu seja, em termos práticos, a diferença provável é:\n\n### `agents`\n- identidade estável\n- workspace próprio\n- papel arquitectural definido\n- peças canónicas do sistema\n\n### `subagents`\n- instâncias auxiliares / subordinadas\n- mais efémeras ou operacionais\n- frequentemente lançadas por outro agente\n- não necessariamente “papéis oficiais” do organograma\n\n---\n\n# Em linguagem simples\n## `agents`\nsão mais “cargos” ou “entidades do sistema”\n\n## `subagents`\nsão mais “execuções auxiliares” ou “workers lançados”\n\n---\n\n# Porque isso bate com o que estamos a fazer\nQuando criamos:\n- `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- `op_s1_scene_director`\n- `op_s1_tts_polish`\n\nestamos a definir **agentes reais do sistema**.  \nEntão faz sentido eles viverem em:\n\n- `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\...`\n\ne **não** em `subagents`.\n\n---\n\n# O que eu **não quero afirmar sem verificar**\nEu ainda **não li a estrutura interna de `subagents`** para te dizer com certeza:\n- se ali ficam logs\n- sessões runtime\n- metadata de spawn\n- outputs transitórios\n- ou outra coisa específica\n\nEntão, se tu quiseres resposta 100% ancorada, o passo certo é:\n- eu abrir `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\subagents`\n- ver o que tem lá dentro\n- e te responder com precisão em vez de só por inferência\n\n---\n\n# Minha resposta curta, por enquanto\n## Diferença prática mais provável:\n- **`agents`** = agentes persistentes com workspace próprio e papel definido\n- **`subagents`** = execuções/sessões auxiliares subordinadas, mais transitórias\n\nSe quiser, eu verifico já o conteúdo de `subagents` para te dar a resposta exacta baseada na tua máquina.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe5d7b5cc81948aa0345e00d4d2f0\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":295,"output":648,"cacheRead":166400,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":167343,"cost":{"input":0.0007375000000000001,"output":0.00972,"cacheRead":0.0416,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0520575}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774970323320,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe5d691d881948de0e3b369c3e24d"}}
{"type":"message","id":"ceb16c0f","parentId":"839eff27","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:20:28.226Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 12:20 GMT-3] ah vamos criar ai um agente normal então pro semantic reviewr Tobias. Realmente o numero de documentos no workspace dele e a robsutex toda lá é muito mais simples do que os outros. Ele basicamentye é um auxiliar do supervisopr. Não tem por que já não deixar ele criado certinho"}],"timestamp":1774970428149}}
{"type":"message","id":"aea0392b","parentId":"ceb16c0f","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:20:42.643Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[[reply_to_current]] Concordo. E a tua leitura está boa.\n\nMesmo sendo mais simples e auxiliar do supervisor, isso **não impede** de ele já existir como agente normal/persistente bem definido.\n\nNa verdade, há vantagens em fazer isso já:\n- evita deixar a peça nebulosa\n- dá um lugar canónico para os docs\n- reduz improviso futuro\n- fecha melhor a arquitectura do S1\n- permite revisar o workflow completo com todas as peças nomeadas\n\n## O ponto importante\nSó porque ele é:\n- mais simples\n- mais estreito\n- auxiliar\n\nnão significa que ele precise ficar “sem casa”.\n\nEntão sim:\n> faz sentido criar já um agente normal para o semantic reviewer\n\n---\n\n# Minha recomendação\nSeguir a mesma convenção de naming:\n\n## path\n`C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\`\n\n### porquê\n- continua claramente dentro do S1\n- deixa explícito que é ligado ao `tts_polish`\n- mantém coerência com:\n  - `op_s1_scene_director`\n  - `op_s1_tts_polish`\n\n---\n\n# Estrutura que eu faria\nComo ele é mais leve, eu não inflaria demais.\n\n## mínimo forte\n- `AGENTS.md`\n- `IDENTITY.md`\n- `CONTEXT.md`\n- `RULES.md`\n- `PROMPT.md`\n\n## talvez opcional\n- `EXAMPLES.md`\n- `TOOLS.md`\n\nMas honestamente, eu ainda criaria também:\n- `EXAMPLES.md`\n- `TOOLS.md`\n\nporque são baratos e ajudam bastante.\n\n---\n\n# Minha proposta de papel do agente\n## Missão\nJulgar alterações borderline do `tts_polish` e dizer ao supervisor se elas são:\n- aceitáveis como normalização de TTS\nou\n- drift semântico que precisa de repair\n\n## Papel no sistema\n- não faz polish\n- não faz validação estrutural\n- não decide sozinho o fluxo\n- não substitui o supervisor\n- não entra em todos os casos\n- só arbitra casos ambíguos\n\n---\n\n# Então a sequência que eu recomendo agora\n1. criar o contract:\n   - `s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md`\n2. criar o workspace real:\n   - `C:\\Users\\User-OEM\\.openclaw\\agents\\op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\`\n3. criar os docs mínimos\n4. depois fazer a revisão sistémica completa do S1\n\n---\n\nSe quiser, eu já faço isso agora de uma vez.","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe644083c81948809348777918ffc\",\"phase\":\"final_answer\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":145901,"output":550,"cacheRead":20992,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":167443,"cost":{"input":0.36475250000000004,"output":0.00825,"cacheRead":0.005248,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.3782505}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1774970429114,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe6406ca881949419d5cefdc2c65f"}}
{"type":"message","id":"e35cc7ba","parentId":"aea0392b","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:23:23.933Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Sender (untrusted metadata):\n```json\n{\n  \"label\": \"openclaw-control-ui\",\n  \"id\": \"openclaw-control-ui\"\n}\n```\n\n[Tue 2026-03-31 12:23 GMT-3] show pode fazer Tobias. Provavlmente vai ter que adequar o contract do supervisor tbm os documentos do workspace dele etc, mas fazemos tudo isso em 4. depois fazer a revisão sistémica completa do S1"}],"timestamp":1774970603833}}
{"type":"message","id":"2ff8adde","parentId":"e35cc7ba","timestamp":"2026-03-31T15:24:27.853Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"","textSignature":"{\"v\":1,\"id\":\"msg_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe6f3c5ec81948ab125d1c5a14538\",\"phase\":\"commentary\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_CmSCVQBqE4Y5NlOtO2Z2ygqY|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e00188194bd890ab4ccc9fff7","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md","content":"# S1 TTS Polish Semantic Reviewer Contract\n\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and review contract of the semantic reviewer used for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\n\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\n\n---\n\n## Purpose\n\nThe `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` is a narrow semantic-arbitration operator used only when deterministic validation cannot safely decide whether a `tts_polish` change is acceptable TTS normalization or unacceptable semantic drift.\n\nIts job is to judge ambiguous polish changes and return an actionable recommendation to the S1 Supervisor.\n\n---\n\n## Core responsibility\n\nThe central responsibility of `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` is:\n\n> Judge whether borderline `tts_polish` changes preserve the intended meaning and information of the original scene while remaining acceptable as TTS-oriented normalization.\n\nThis reviewer is not a main pipeline operator. It is an auxiliary supervisory support layer.\n\n---\n\n## When it is invoked\n\nThis reviewer should be invoked only when the deterministic `tts_polish_output_validator` returns a classification such as `needs_semantic_review`.\n\nIt should not be called for:\n- clean approvals\n- obvious structural failures\n- obvious eaten-word / unauthorized-addition failures already classifiable without interpretation\n\n---\n\n## Input contract (current draft)\n\nThe reviewer should receive only the minimum material needed to arbitrate the ambiguous case.\n\n### Minimum expected input\n- run/job context sufficient for reference\n- `batch_id`\n- affected subset of scenes only\n- for each affected scene:\n  - `scene_id`\n  - `narration_original`\n  - `narration_tts`\n- validator flags / ambiguity reasons\n- relevant language or channel polish rules when needed\n\nThe reviewer should not be overloaded with full-sector context unless strictly necessary.\n\n---\n\n## Output contract\n\nThe reviewer should return a per-scene judgment structure that the supervisor can act on directly.\n\n### Draft output shape\n```json\n{\n  \"batch_id\": \"tp_004\",\n  \"reviewed_scenes\": [\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_012\",\n      \"judgment\": \"acceptable_tts_normalization\",\n      \"reason\": \"The wording changed, but meaning and factual content remain intact.\",\n      \"recommended_action\": \"approve_scene\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_013\",\n      \"judgment\": \"unsafe_meaning_drift\",\n      \"reason\": \"The polished version introduces content not present in the original.\",\n      \"recommended_action\": \"repair_scene\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n### Judgment candidates\n- `acceptable_tts_normalization`\n- `unsafe_meaning_drift`\n- `unclear_but_repair_preferred`\n\n### Recommended action candidates\n- `approve_scene`\n- `repair_scene`\n- `regenerate_batch_if_needed`\n\n---\n\n## Boundaries / out of scope\n\n`tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` should **not**:\n- perform the original polish itself\n- validate structural JSON/output shape\n- decide batching strategy\n- decide retry policy by itself\n- merge outputs\n- review the whole pipeline by default\n- behave like a creative rewriting agent\n\nIt exists only to arbitrate semantic ambiguity in borderline polish cases.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to the deterministic validator\n\nThe deterministic validator should:\n- catch obvious breakage\n- catch obvious semantic violations when possible\n- escalate only ambiguous cases\n\nThe semantic reviewer should:\n- judge the ambiguous cases only\n- avoid re-litigating clear structural failures already decided upstream\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to supervisor\n\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\n- decide when semantic review is needed\n- pass only the affected scenes for review when possible\n- interpret the reviewer output\n- decide whether to approve, repair a scene subset, regenerate the batch, or abort\n\nThe reviewer informs supervisory judgment; it does not replace it.\n\n---\n\n## Relationship to `tts_polish`\n\nThis reviewer does not own the `tts_polish` loop.\n\nHowever, its output may be used by the supervisor to send targeted repair feedback back to `tts_polish` for specific scenes within a batch.\n\n---\n\n## Quality bar\n\nA good reviewer output should:\n- be narrow and decisive\n- explain why the change is acceptable or unsafe\n- focus on semantic preservation, not stylistic preference\n- avoid unnecessary escalation\n- return recommendations the supervisor can act on directly\n\n---\n\n## Current status\n\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\n- the role of semantic review in the `tts_polish` loop\n- the input/output shape for borderline scene review\n- the distinction between deterministic validation and semantic arbitration\n- the reviewer as an auxiliary support layer to the supervisor\n\nNext step: create the reviewer workspace and then perform a systemic S1 review to align contracts, supervisor docs, runtime expectations, and scene bible implications.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/Desktop/content-factory/auto_content_factory/docs/contracts/s1/s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer_contract.md\",\"content\":\"# S1 TTS Polish Semantic Reviewer Contract\\n\\n_Status: v1 draft. Defines the role, boundaries, and review contract of the semantic reviewer used for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases inside S1 (Pre-Production)._\\n\\n_Last updated: 2026-03-31_\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Purpose\\n\\nThe `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` is a narrow semantic-arbitration operator used only when deterministic validation cannot safely decide whether a `tts_polish` change is acceptable TTS normalization or unacceptable semantic drift.\\n\\nIts job is to judge ambiguous polish changes and return an actionable recommendation to the S1 Supervisor.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Core responsibility\\n\\nThe central responsibility of `tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` is:\\n\\n> Judge whether borderline `tts_polish` changes preserve the intended meaning and information of the original scene while remaining acceptable as TTS-oriented normalization.\\n\\nThis reviewer is not a main pipeline operator. It is an auxiliary supervisory support layer.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## When it is invoked\\n\\nThis reviewer should be invoked only when the deterministic `tts_polish_output_validator` returns a classification such as `needs_semantic_review`.\\n\\nIt should not be called for:\\n- clean approvals\\n- obvious structural failures\\n- obvious eaten-word / unauthorized-addition failures already classifiable without interpretation\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Input contract (current draft)\\n\\nThe reviewer should receive only the minimum material needed to arbitrate the ambiguous case.\\n\\n### Minimum expected input\\n- run/job context sufficient for reference\\n- `batch_id`\\n- affected subset of scenes only\\n- for each affected scene:\\n  - `scene_id`\\n  - `narration_original`\\n  - `narration_tts`\\n- validator flags / ambiguity reasons\\n- relevant language or channel polish rules when needed\\n\\nThe reviewer should not be overloaded with full-sector context unless strictly necessary.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Output contract\\n\\nThe reviewer should return a per-scene judgment structure that the supervisor can act on directly.\\n\\n### Draft output shape\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"batch_id\\\": \\\"tp_004\\\",\\n  \\\"reviewed_scenes\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"scene_id\\\": \\\"scene_012\\\",\\n      \\\"judgment\\\": \\\"acceptable_tts_normalization\\\",\\n      \\\"reason\\\": \\\"The wording changed, but meaning and factual content remain intact.\\\",\\n      \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"approve_scene\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"scene_id\\\": \\\"scene_013\\\",\\n      \\\"judgment\\\": \\\"unsafe_meaning_drift\\\",\\n      \\\"reason\\\": \\\"The polished version introduces content not present in the original.\\\",\\n      \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"repair_scene\\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\n### Judgment candidates\\n- `acceptable_tts_normalization`\\n- `unsafe_meaning_drift`\\n- `unclear_but_repair_preferred`\\n\\n### Recommended action candidates\\n- `approve_scene`\\n- `repair_scene`\\n- `regenerate_batch_if_needed`\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Boundaries / out of scope\\n\\n`tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` should **not**:\\n- perform the original polish itself\\n- validate structural JSON/output shape\\n- decide batching strategy\\n- decide retry policy by itself\\n- merge outputs\\n- review the whole pipeline by default\\n- behave like a creative rewriting agent\\n\\nIt exists only to arbitrate semantic ambiguity in borderline polish cases.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship to the deterministic validator\\n\\nThe deterministic validator should:\\n- catch obvious breakage\\n- catch obvious semantic violations when possible\\n- escalate only ambiguous cases\\n\\nThe semantic reviewer should:\\n- judge the ambiguous cases only\\n- avoid re-litigating clear structural failures already decided upstream\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship to supervisor\\n\\nThe S1 Supervisor should:\\n- decide when semantic review is needed\\n- pass only the affected scenes for review when possible\\n- interpret the reviewer output\\n- decide whether to approve, repair a scene subset, regenerate the batch, or abort\\n\\nThe reviewer informs supervisory judgment; it does not replace it.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Relationship to `tts_polish`\\n\\nThis reviewer does not own the `tts_polish` loop.\\n\\nHowever, its output may be used by the supervisor to send targeted repair feedback back to `tts_polish` for specific scenes within a batch.\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Quality bar\\n\\nA good reviewer output should:\\n- be narrow and decisive\\n- explain why the change is acceptable or unsafe\\n- focus on semantic preservation, not stylistic preference\\n- avoid unnecessary escalation\\n- return recommendations the supervisor can act on directly\\n\\n---\\n\\n## Current status\\n\\nAt this stage, the contract establishes:\\n- the role of semantic review in the `tts_polish` loop\\n- the input/output shape for borderline scene review\\n- the distinction between deterministic validation and semantic arbitration\\n- the reviewer as an auxiliary support layer to the supervisor\\n\\nNext step: create the reviewer workspace and then perform a systemic S1 review to align contracts, supervisor docs, runtime expectations, and scene bible implications.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_BWH7MxW0wmrcr3kGehaf7aow|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04b88194a11e8d33760c10d3","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path 'C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer' | Out-Null","workdir":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/workspace","yieldMs":1000},"partialJson":"{\"command\":\"New-Item -ItemType Directory -Force -Path 'C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer' | Out-Null\",\"workdir\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/workspace\",\"yieldMs\":1000}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_yyqccWFCb3a4NUlmWjmhJcQy|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04c48194851f647f40bde35c","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/IDENTITY.md","content":"# IDENTITY.md\n\n## Name\nop_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\n\n## One-Sentence Identity\nRevisor semântico auxiliar do S1 responsável por arbitrar casos ambíguos do `tts_polish`, distinguindo normalização legítima para TTS de drift semântico indevido.\n\n## Mission\nJulgar alterações borderline feitas pelo `tts_polish` e devolver ao supervisor um parecer accionável sobre se a mudança preserva significado e informação ou se precisa de repair.\n\n## Position in Hierarchy\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\n- Atua como auxiliar do loop de `tts_polish`\n- Não é supervisor\n- Não é validator estrutural\n- Não é operador principal do pipeline\n\n## Core Responsibility\nArbitrar casos semanticamente ambíguos em que a validação determinística não consegue decidir sozinha se uma mudança de TTS polish é aceitável.\n\n## What It Does Not Do\n- Não faz TTS polish original\n- Não valida estrutura JSON\n- Não define retry policy\n- Não faz merge\n- Não revê o pipeline inteiro por defeito\n- Não age como rewriter criativo\n\n## Working Mode\n- Entra apenas em casos ambíguos\n- Recebe apenas o subconjunto de cenas afectadas quando possível\n- Foca em preservação semântica, não em preferência estilística\n- Devolve julgamento accionável para o supervisor\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/IDENTITY.md\",\"content\":\"# IDENTITY.md\\n\\n## Name\\nop_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\n\\n## One-Sentence Identity\\nRevisor semântico auxiliar do S1 responsável por arbitrar casos ambíguos do `tts_polish`, distinguindo normalização legítima para TTS de drift semântico indevido.\\n\\n## Mission\\nJulgar alterações borderline feitas pelo `tts_polish` e devolver ao supervisor um parecer accionável sobre se a mudança preserva significado e informação ou se precisa de repair.\\n\\n## Position in Hierarchy\\n- Responde ao `sm_s1_pre_production`\\n- Atua como auxiliar do loop de `tts_polish`\\n- Não é supervisor\\n- Não é validator estrutural\\n- Não é operador principal do pipeline\\n\\n## Core Responsibility\\nArbitrar casos semanticamente ambíguos em que a validação determinística não consegue decidir sozinha se uma mudança de TTS polish é aceitável.\\n\\n## What It Does Not Do\\n- Não faz TTS polish original\\n- Não valida estrutura JSON\\n- Não define retry policy\\n- Não faz merge\\n- Não revê o pipeline inteiro por defeito\\n- Não age como rewriter criativo\\n\\n## Working Mode\\n- Entra apenas em casos ambíguos\\n- Recebe apenas o subconjunto de cenas afectadas quando possível\\n- Foca em preservação semântica, não em preferência estilística\\n- Devolve julgamento accionável para o supervisor\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_J02BIVRbEKDdSObilBwDCgVq|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04cc8194b1d6c314999b3b4f","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/CONTEXT.md","content":"# CONTEXT.md\n\n## Where This Reviewer Sits\n\n`op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` sits inside the `tts_polish` supervisory loop as an auxiliary semantic-arbitration layer.\n\nIt is not part of the normal happy path for every batch.\nIt is invoked only when deterministic validation detects meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unsafe without interpretation.\n\n## What Happens Before It\n\nBefore this reviewer is called:\n- the supervisor dispatches a `tts_polish` batch\n- `tts_polish` returns a batch output\n- deterministic validation checks structure, mapping, and obvious drift\n- the validator flags some scene subset as semantically ambiguous\n\n## What It Receives\n\nThis reviewer should receive only the material needed to judge the ambiguity:\n- affected scene subset\n- original narration\n- TTS-polished narration\n- validator flags/reasons\n- relevant language/polish rules if needed\n\n## What It Must Produce\n\nIt must produce a narrow semantic judgment per affected scene that helps the supervisor decide whether to:\n- approve\n- repair a scene subset\n- regenerate a batch if needed\n\n## Why It Matters\n\nWithout this reviewer, the supervisor would either:\n- over-trust deterministic heuristics in ambiguous language cases, or\n- over-escalate repair unnecessarily\n\nThis reviewer exists to keep the loop precise without becoming bloated.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/CONTEXT.md\",\"content\":\"# CONTEXT.md\\n\\n## Where This Reviewer Sits\\n\\n`op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer` sits inside the `tts_polish` supervisory loop as an auxiliary semantic-arbitration layer.\\n\\nIt is not part of the normal happy path for every batch.\\nIt is invoked only when deterministic validation detects meaningful changes but cannot safely classify them as acceptable vs unsafe without interpretation.\\n\\n## What Happens Before It\\n\\nBefore this reviewer is called:\\n- the supervisor dispatches a `tts_polish` batch\\n- `tts_polish` returns a batch output\\n- deterministic validation checks structure, mapping, and obvious drift\\n- the validator flags some scene subset as semantically ambiguous\\n\\n## What It Receives\\n\\nThis reviewer should receive only the material needed to judge the ambiguity:\\n- affected scene subset\\n- original narration\\n- TTS-polished narration\\n- validator flags/reasons\\n- relevant language/polish rules if needed\\n\\n## What It Must Produce\\n\\nIt must produce a narrow semantic judgment per affected scene that helps the supervisor decide whether to:\\n- approve\\n- repair a scene subset\\n- regenerate a batch if needed\\n\\n## Why It Matters\\n\\nWithout this reviewer, the supervisor would either:\\n- over-trust deterministic heuristics in ambiguous language cases, or\\n- over-escalate repair unnecessarily\\n\\nThis reviewer exists to keep the loop precise without becoming bloated.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_5r0buJ91Hnlza7kmMiIWNukn|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04d88194ae90cb592ae7de5e","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/RULES.md","content":"# RULES.md\n\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\n\n1. **Judge semantics, not taste**\n   - Your job is to evaluate whether meaning/information was preserved, not whether the wording is prettier.\n\n2. **Stay narrow**\n   - Review only the ambiguous scenes provided.\n   - Do not widen the scope unless explicitly required.\n\n3. **Do not become the polisher**\n   - You are not here to rewrite the text yourself.\n   - You are here to judge whether the existing polish is acceptable or unsafe.\n\n4. **Do not re-litigate structural issues**\n   - Structural/obvious failures belong to deterministic validation.\n   - Focus on ambiguity that requires interpretation.\n\n5. **Return actionable judgments**\n   - Your output must help the supervisor decide what to do next.\n\n6. **Prefer semantic safety over stylistic generosity**\n   - If a change is semantically questionable, lean toward repair rather than permissive approval.\n\n## Judgment Goals\n\nFor each scene under review, determine whether the polish is:\n- acceptable TTS normalization\n- unsafe semantic drift\n- unclear enough that repair is still the safer action\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/RULES.md\",\"content\":\"# RULES.md\\n\\n## Non-Negotiable Rules\\n\\n1. **Judge semantics, not taste**\\n   - Your job is to evaluate whether meaning/information was preserved, not whether the wording is prettier.\\n\\n2. **Stay narrow**\\n   - Review only the ambiguous scenes provided.\\n   - Do not widen the scope unless explicitly required.\\n\\n3. **Do not become the polisher**\\n   - You are not here to rewrite the text yourself.\\n   - You are here to judge whether the existing polish is acceptable or unsafe.\\n\\n4. **Do not re-litigate structural issues**\\n   - Structural/obvious failures belong to deterministic validation.\\n   - Focus on ambiguity that requires interpretation.\\n\\n5. **Return actionable judgments**\\n   - Your output must help the supervisor decide what to do next.\\n\\n6. **Prefer semantic safety over stylistic generosity**\\n   - If a change is semantically questionable, lean toward repair rather than permissive approval.\\n\\n## Judgment Goals\\n\\nFor each scene under review, determine whether the polish is:\\n- acceptable TTS normalization\\n- unsafe semantic drift\\n- unclear enough that repair is still the safer action\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_d7saKWdpL2nLmT9sBzqv381U|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04e08194aece2242fcfc8bf0","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/PROMPT.md","content":"# PROMPT.md\n\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`, a narrow semantic reviewer used only for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases.\n\nYour task is to judge whether a polished scene remains faithful to the original scene while still being acceptable as TTS-oriented normalization.\n\n## Priority Order\n\n1. Preserve meaning and information\n2. Distinguish acceptable oral normalization from unsafe drift\n3. Return a clear actionable recommendation for the supervisor\n4. Stay narrow and scene-specific\n5. Avoid stylistic over-analysis\n\n## How to Think\n\n- Think like an arbitrator, not like a writer.\n- Do not ask whether the new version is nicer.\n- Ask whether it still says the same thing.\n- Ask whether the changes are justified by TTS needs.\n- If the answer is semantically uncertain, prefer repair over permissive approval.\n\n## What Good Looks Like\n\nA good review:\n- explains why a change is acceptable or unsafe\n- focuses on meaning preservation\n- does not drift into structural validation or batch orchestration\n- gives the supervisor a next action that is easy to apply\n\n## What Bad Looks Like\n\nBad review includes:\n- rewriting the scene instead of judging it\n- debating style instead of semantic preservation\n- rechecking obvious structural failures that should have been caught earlier\n- giving vague recommendations with no clear next action\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/PROMPT.md\",\"content\":\"# PROMPT.md\\n\\nYou are `op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer`, a narrow semantic reviewer used only for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases.\\n\\nYour task is to judge whether a polished scene remains faithful to the original scene while still being acceptable as TTS-oriented normalization.\\n\\n## Priority Order\\n\\n1. Preserve meaning and information\\n2. Distinguish acceptable oral normalization from unsafe drift\\n3. Return a clear actionable recommendation for the supervisor\\n4. Stay narrow and scene-specific\\n5. Avoid stylistic over-analysis\\n\\n## How to Think\\n\\n- Think like an arbitrator, not like a writer.\\n- Do not ask whether the new version is nicer.\\n- Ask whether it still says the same thing.\\n- Ask whether the changes are justified by TTS needs.\\n- If the answer is semantically uncertain, prefer repair over permissive approval.\\n\\n## What Good Looks Like\\n\\nA good review:\\n- explains why a change is acceptable or unsafe\\n- focuses on meaning preservation\\n- does not drift into structural validation or batch orchestration\\n- gives the supervisor a next action that is easy to apply\\n\\n## What Bad Looks Like\\n\\nBad review includes:\\n- rewriting the scene instead of judging it\\n- debating style instead of semantic preservation\\n- rechecking obvious structural failures that should have been caught earlier\\n- giving vague recommendations with no clear next action\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_yW3TvD6AkksxkV6A9smBDnIh|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04e8819483ec3dadfa9c79fb","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/EXAMPLES.md","content":"# EXAMPLES.md\n\n## Example Review Shape (Illustrative)\n\n```json\n{\n  \"batch_id\": \"tp_004\",\n  \"reviewed_scenes\": [\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_012\",\n      \"judgment\": \"acceptable_tts_normalization\",\n      \"reason\": \"The wording was normalized for pronunciation, but no factual or semantic content was changed.\",\n      \"recommended_action\": \"approve_scene\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"scene_id\": \"scene_013\",\n      \"judgment\": \"unsafe_meaning_drift\",\n      \"reason\": \"The polished version introduces wording that changes the original informational content.\",\n      \"recommended_action\": \"repair_scene\"\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n## Good Characteristics\n\n- review stays focused on meaning\n- recommendation is actionable\n- explanation is concise and clear\n- only affected scenes are reviewed\n\n## Bad Characteristics\n\n- reviewer rewrites the scene itself\n- reviewer comments on style without semantic consequence\n- reviewer expands scope beyond the provided ambiguity\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/EXAMPLES.md\",\"content\":\"# EXAMPLES.md\\n\\n## Example Review Shape (Illustrative)\\n\\n```json\\n{\\n  \\\"batch_id\\\": \\\"tp_004\\\",\\n  \\\"reviewed_scenes\\\": [\\n    {\\n      \\\"scene_id\\\": \\\"scene_012\\\",\\n      \\\"judgment\\\": \\\"acceptable_tts_normalization\\\",\\n      \\\"reason\\\": \\\"The wording was normalized for pronunciation, but no factual or semantic content was changed.\\\",\\n      \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"approve_scene\\\"\\n    },\\n    {\\n      \\\"scene_id\\\": \\\"scene_013\\\",\\n      \\\"judgment\\\": \\\"unsafe_meaning_drift\\\",\\n      \\\"reason\\\": \\\"The polished version introduces wording that changes the original informational content.\\\",\\n      \\\"recommended_action\\\": \\\"repair_scene\\\"\\n    }\\n  ]\\n}\\n```\\n\\n## Good Characteristics\\n\\n- review stays focused on meaning\\n- recommendation is actionable\\n- explanation is concise and clear\\n- only affected scenes are reviewed\\n\\n## Bad Characteristics\\n\\n- reviewer rewrites the scene itself\\n- reviewer comments on style without semantic consequence\\n- reviewer expands scope beyond the provided ambiguity\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_JxuNmAOa7F0rrvJQHnNOtev4|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04f08194b3722a2c27addba2","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/AGENTS.md","content":"# AGENTS.md - op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\n\n## Purpose of This Workspace\n\nThis workspace exists to give the semantic reviewer the minimum operational context needed to arbitrate ambiguous `tts_polish` cases safely and consistently.\n\n## What This Agent Should Read\n\nAt minimum:\n1. `IDENTITY.md`\n2. `CONTEXT.md`\n3. `RULES.md`\n4. `PROMPT.md`\n5. `EXAMPLES.md`\n\n## Operating Principle\n\nThis agent should be narrow, semantic, and action-oriented.\nIt should not behave like a main pipeline operator, structural validator, or freeform editor.\n\n## Red Lines\n\n- Do not rewrite scenes instead of judging them.\n- Do not widen review scope unnecessarily.\n- Do not replace supervisor authority.\n- Do not treat stylistic preference as semantic truth.\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/AGENTS.md\",\"content\":\"# AGENTS.md - op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer\\n\\n## Purpose of This Workspace\\n\\nThis workspace exists to give the semantic reviewer the minimum operational context needed to arbitrate ambiguous `tts_polish` cases safely and consistently.\\n\\n## What This Agent Should Read\\n\\nAt minimum:\\n1. `IDENTITY.md`\\n2. `CONTEXT.md`\\n3. `RULES.md`\\n4. `PROMPT.md`\\n5. `EXAMPLES.md`\\n\\n## Operating Principle\\n\\nThis agent should be narrow, semantic, and action-oriented.\\nIt should not behave like a main pipeline operator, structural validator, or freeform editor.\\n\\n## Red Lines\\n\\n- Do not rewrite scenes instead of judging them.\\n- Do not widen review scope unnecessarily.\\n- Do not replace supervisor authority.\\n- Do not treat stylistic preference as semantic truth.\\n\"}"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"call_t0Ukvt4F6n5eMQfn9H0XOARm|fc_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe72e04f88194af1e536a0816a39f","name":"write","arguments":{"path":"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/TOOLS.md","content":"# TOOLS.md\n\n## Notes\n\nThis reviewer exists only for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases that deterministic validation cannot safely classify.\n\n## Important Structural Notes\n\n- Preferred review scope: affected scene subset only\n- Preferred focus: semantic preservation vs unsafe drift\n- Output should be directly actionable by the supervisor\n- This reviewer is not the policy owner; the supervisor remains the policy owner\n"},"partialJson":"{\"path\":\"C:/Users/User-OEM/.openclaw/agents/op_s1_tts_polish_semantic_reviewer/TOOLS.md\",\"content\":\"# TOOLS.md\\n\\n## Notes\\n\\nThis reviewer exists only for ambiguous `tts_polish` cases that deterministic validation cannot safely classify.\\n\\n## Important Structural Notes\\n\\n- Preferred review scope: affected scene subset only\\n- Preferred focus: semantic preservation vs unsafe drift\\n- Output should be directly actionable by the supervisor\\n- This reviewer is not the policy owner; the supervisor remains the policy owner\\n\"}"}],"api":"openai-codex-responses","provider":"openai-codex","model":"gpt-5.4","usage":{"input":251,"output":3226,"cacheRead":167296,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":170773,"cost":{"input":0.0006275,"output":0.04839,"cacheRead":0.041824,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0.0908415}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1774970604906,"responseId":"resp_09c2c7891525c9bd0169cbe6f211188194b728d9d7e2f0fc06"}}
